mber 6, 1998\n|term_end4     = November 14, 2002\n|predecessor4  = [[Eric Johnson (Georgia politician)|Eric Johnson]]\n|successor4    = [[Robert Brown (Georgia politician)|Robert Brown]]\n|state_senate5 = Georgia\n|term_start5   = January 3, 1997\n|term_end5     = January 3, 2005\n|district5     = 56th\n|predecessor5  = Sallie Newbill\n|successor5    = [[Dan Moody (Georgia politician)|Dan Moody]]\n|birth_name    = Thomas Edmunds Price\n|birth_date    = {{birth date and age|1954|10|8}}\n|birth_place   = [[Lansing, Michigan]], U.S.\n|death_date    =\n|death_place   =\n|party         = [[Republican Party (United States)|Republican]]\n|spouse        = [[Betty Price (politician)|Betty Clark]]\n|children      = 1\n|education     = [[University of Michigan]] ([[Bachelor of Arts|B.A.]], [[Doctor of Medicine|M.D.]])\n|net_worth     = $10 million<ref>{{cite news |title=Here's What Each Member Of Trump's $4.5 Billion Cabinet Is Worth |url=https://www.forbes.com/sites/chasewithorn/2016/12/22/heres-how-much-trumps-cabinet-is-really-worth/#3b5c6faf7169 |first=Chase |last=Peterson-Withorn |publisher=[[Forbes]] |date=December 22, 2016}}</ref>\n}}\n'''Thomas Edmunds Price''' (born October 8, 1954) is an American physician and politician who served as the [[United States Secretary of Health and Human Services]] in the administration of [[Donald Trump]] from February to September, 2017, and who was the [[United States House of Representatives|U.S. Representative]] for {{ushr|GA|6}}, encompassing the northern suburbs of [[Atlanta]], from 2005 to 2017.<ref name=baker>{{cite news |last1=Baker |first1=Peter |last2=Thrush |first2=Glenn|last3=Haberman |first3=Maggie |date=September 29, 2017 |title=Health Secretary Tom Price Resigns After Drawing Ire for Chartered Flights |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2017/09/29/us/politics/tom-price-trump-hhs.html |work=[[The New York Times]] |location=New York |access-date=September 30, 2017 }}</ref>\n\nWhile in Congress, Price chaired the [[United States House Committee on the Budget|House Committee on the Budget]],<ref>{{cite web |url=http://budget.house.gov/about/budgetcommitteemembers.htm |title=Budget Committee Members |publisher=[[United States House Committee on the Budget]] |accessdate=March 18, 2013 |deadurl=yes |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130317071723/http://budget.house.gov/about/budgetcommitteemembers.htm |archivedate=March 17, 2013 |df=mdy-all }}</ref> [[Republican Study Committee]] and [[Steering and Policy Committees of the United States House of Representatives|Republican Policy Committee]].<ref name=\"The Hill\">{{cite news |last1=Lillis|first1=Mike |title=GOP policy leader Price: 'More cuts and more reforms are on the way'|url=http://thehill.com/homenews/house/145261-gop-policy-leader-price-more-cuts-and-more-reforms-are-on-the-way |publisher=[[The Hill (newspaper)|The Hill]] | date=February 19, 2011}}</ref><ref name=\"Peach Pundit\">{{cite news|last1=Harper|first1=Charlie|title=Tom Price Elected Chairman Of House Republican Policy Committee | url=http://www.peachpundit.com/2010/11/18/tom-price-elected-chairman-of-house-republican-policy-committee/ |work=Peach Pundit |date=November 18, 2010}}</ref> On September 29, 2017, he resigned as head of [[United States Department of Health and Human Services|HHS]] following criticism of his use of private charters and military aircraft for travel.<ref name=baker/> In July 2018, the HHS inspector general urged the HHS to recoup at least $341,000 from Price for wasteful expenditures.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.politico.com/story/2018/07/13/tom-price-auditor-travel-685778|title=Federal auditor calls for recouping $341K Tom Price spent on flights|work=POLITICO|access-date=2018-07-14|language=en}}</ref>\n\n==Early life, education, and medical career==\nPrice was born in [[Lansing, Michigan]], and grew up in [[Dearborn, Michigan|Dearborn]], where he attended Adams Jr. High and [[Dearborn High School]].<ref name=\":1\">{{Cite news|url=http://www.detroitnews.com/story/news/local/michigan/2016/11/29/tom-price/94602446/|title=Trump's pick for health chief is a Lansing native|work=Detroit News|access-date=2017-03-06|language=en}}</ref><ref name=\"allgov\">{{Cite news|url=http://www.allgov.com/news/top-stories/department-of-health-and-human-services-who-is-tom-price-170109?news=860019|title=Department of Health and Human Services: Who Is Tom Price?|work=AllGov|access-date=2017-03-06}}</ref> Price's father and grandfather were both doctors. As a child, Price occasionally accompanied his grandfather on [[house calls]] in [[Toledo, Ohio]]. Until Price was the age of six, his father worked a [[dairy farm]] in [[Fowlerville, Michigan]].<ref name=\"New Voices\">{{cite web|url=http://go.galegroup.com/ps/retrieve.do?tabID=T004&resultListType=RESULT_LIST&searchResultsType=SingleTab&searchType=AdvancedSearchForm&currentPosition=1&docId=GALE%7CA125858045&docType=Article&sort=Relevance&contentSegment=&prodId=STND&contentSet=GALE%7CA125858045&searchId=R1&userGroupName=fairfax_main&inPS=true|author=Mark Bixler|title=Georgia's New Voices in Washington / Tom Price: Surgeon Takes Sharp Mind, Doctors' Cause to D.C.|work=The Atlanta Journal-Constitution|date=December 7, 2004|accessdate=October 13, 2017}} {{subscription required|via=Infotrac Newsstand}}</ref>\n\nPrice received his [[Bachelor of Arts|B.A.]] (1975) and [[Doctor of Medicine|M.D.]] (1979) degrees from the [[University of Michigan]].<ref name=\":1\" /> He completed a residency in orthopedic surgery at [[Emory University]] in Atlanta, and settled in the suburb of [[Roswell, Georgia]].<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://northfulton.com/stories/Candidate-Betty-Clark-Price,75391|title=Candidate: Betty Clark Price|work=Appen Media Group|access-date=2017-03-06|language=en}}</ref>\n\nPrice began private practice in 1984 and returned to Emory as an assistant professor of [[orthopedic surgery]] in 2002.<ref name=\"allgov\"/><ref>{{cite web|url=http://news.emory.edu/stories/2016/11/tom_price_hhs/index.html|author=Quinn Eastman|title=Rep. Price, Doctor with Emory Ties, Tapped for Health and Human Services Secretary|work=Emory News Center|date=November 29, 2016|accessdate=October 13, 2017}} {{subscription required|via=Infortrac Newsstand}}</ref> He was the director of the orthopedic clinic at Atlanta's [[Grady Memorial Hospital]], where he first met his wife [[Betty Price (politician)|Betty]], who worked there as [[anesthesiologist]].<ref name=\"allgov\"/><ref name=\"Fast Facts\">{{Cite news|url=http://heavy.com/news/2016/11/tom-price-secretary-of-health-and-human-services-donald-trump-appointment-nominee-georgia-house-representatives-congress-obamacare-affordable-care-act-repeal-replacement-bill-family-wife-kids/|title=Tom Price: 5 Fast Facts You Need to Know|last=Morrow|first=Brendan|date=2016-11-29|work=Heavy.com|access-date=2017-03-06|language=en-US}}</ref>\n\nPrice is a former member of the [[Association of American Physicians and Surgeons]] (AAPS), a politically conservative non-profit association founded in 1943 to \"fight socialized medicine and to fight the government takeover of medicine.\"<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.esquire.com/news-politics/politics/news/a38354/surprise-new-house-majority-leader-crazy/|title=The GOP's Search for a New House Majority Leader Is a Race to the Bottom|last=Pierce|first=Charles P.|date=September 29, 2015|work=Esquire|access-date=December 27, 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2011/01/19/business/19physicians.html|title=Vocal Physicians Group Renews Health Law Fight|last=Meier|first=Barry|date=January 18, 2011|access-date=December 27, 2016}}</ref> The AAPS opposes [[Medicare (United States)|Medicare]] and mandatory [[vaccination]]. Price is also a member of the [[American Medical Association]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/news/powerpost/wp/2017/02/09/through-views-and-alliances-hhs-nominee-has-long-opposed-government-role-in-health-care/|author=Amy Goldstein|title=Tom Price belongs to a doctors group with unorthodox views on government and health care|work=[[The Washington Post]]|date=February 9, 2017|accessdate=October 11, 2017}}</ref>\n\nBefore entering the state senate, Price was a politically active member of the Republican Party and traveled with the [[Medical Association of Georgia]] in the early 1990s to oppose the [[Clinton health care plan of 1993]].<ref name=\"New Voices\"/>\n\n==Georgia Senate (1996\u20132005)==\n\n===Elections and results===\nPrice first ran for office, after receiving a phone call from [[state senator]] Sallie Newbill in 1995. Newbill, who represented Georgia's 56th senate district, was planning to retire and personally asked Price if he was interested in succeeding her. Price accepted the offer<ref name=\"New Voices\"/> and defeated Democrat Ellen Milholland in the election, 71\u201329%.<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.ourcampaigns.com/RaceDetail.html?RaceID=288507 | title=GA State Senate 56 Race \u2013 Nov 05, 1996 | publisher=Our Campaigns | accessdate=November 19, 2016}}</ref> In a 1998 rematch, he won re-election to a second term by defeating Milholland by a margin of 75\u201325%.<ref>{{cite web| url=http://www.ourcampaigns.com/RaceDetail.html?RaceID=288618|title=GA State Senate 56 Race \u2013 Nov 03, 1998|publisher=Our Campaigns | accessdate=November 19, 2016}}</ref> In 2000 and 2002, he won re-election to a third and fourth term unopposed.<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.ourcampaigns.com/RaceDetail.html?RaceID=288768 | title= GA State Senate 056 Race \u2013 Nov 07, 2000 | publisher=Our Campaigns | accessdate=November 19, 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.ourcampaigns.com/RaceDetail.html?RaceID=288780 | title= GA State Senate 056 Race |date= November 5, 2002 | publisher=Our Campaigns | accessdate=November 19, 2016}}</ref>\n\nPrice has cited discontent with government regulations of the health care industry as his primary reason for becoming involved in politics.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://go.galegroup.com/ps/retrieve.do?tabID=T004&resultListType=RESULT_LIST&searchResultsType=SingleTab&searchType=AdvancedSearchForm&currentPosition=3&docId=GALE%7CA198117900&docType=Article&sort=DA-ASC-SORT&contentSegment=&prodId=STND&contentSet=GALE%7CA198117900&searchId=R2&userGroupName=fairfax_main&inPS=true|author=Bob Keefe|title=GOP Finds its Voice of Opposition in Price: Roswell Congressman Emerges as Among Most Vocal Critics of President|work=[[The Atlanta Journal-Constitution]]|date=April 19, 2009|accessdate=October 10, 2017}} {{subscription required|via=Infotrac Newsstand}}</ref>\n\n===Committee memberships===\nDuring his tenure as state senator, Price served on the committees for Appropriations, Economic Development and Tourism, Education, Ethics, Health and Human Services, Insurance and Labor, Reapportionment and Redistricting, and Rules.<ref name=\"senate.ga.gov\">{{cite web | url=http://www.senate.ga.gov/senators/en-US/member.aspx?Member=329&Session=1| title=Georgia State Senator Tom Price (Republican \u2013 56) | publisher=Georgia State Senate}}</ref>\n\n===Tenure===\nPrice was elected [[minority whip]] of the Georgia state senate on November 6, 1998.<ref name=\"Macon 98\">{{cite news|author=''The Associated Press'' staff|title=GOP Elects Georgia Senate Leaders|work=[[The Macon Telegraph]]|date=November 7, 1998}}</ref> He held this position until November 14, 2002, when Republicans took control of the state senate, and Price was elected [[majority leader]] \u2013 the first Republican to ever hold this position in Georgia.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://go.galegroup.com/ps/retrieve.do?tabID=T004&resultListType=RESULT_LIST&searchResultsType=SingleTab&searchType=AdvancedSearchForm&currentPosition=27&docId=GALE%7CA94244549&docType=Brief+article&sort=DA-ASC-SORT&contentSegment=&prodId=STND&contentSet=GALE%7CA94244549&searchId=R2&userGroupName=fairfax_main&inPS=true|author=James Salzer|title=Republicans Pick Leaders for State Senate Role Reversal|work=The Atlanta Journal-Constitution|date=November 15, 2002|accessdate=October 9, 2017}} {{subscription required|via=Infotrac Newsstand}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://go.galegroup.com/ps/retrieve.do?tabID=T004&resultListType=RESULT_LIST&searchResultsType=SingleTab&searchType=AdvancedSearchForm&currentPosition=28&docId=GALE%7CA94302905&docType=Article&sort=DA-ASC-SORT&contentSegment=&prodId=STND&contentSet=GALE%7CA94302905&searchId=R2&userGroupName=fairfax_main&inPS=true|author1=Jim Galloway|author2=James Salzer|author3=Jim Tharpe|title=Legislative Leaders for 2003 Session|work=The Atlanta Journal-Constitution|date=November 17, 2002|accessdate=October 9, 2017}} {{subscription required|via=Infotrac Newsstand}}</ref><ref name=\"myAJC\">{{cite web|url=http://www.myajc.com/news/state--regional-govt--politics/tom-price-the-georgia-lawmaker-who-will-lead-trump-health-policy/zuBYBN5nw4UmIehW4MnQ9I/|author1=Greg Bluestein|author2=Tamar Hallerman|title=Tom Price: The Georgia lawmaker who will lead Trump's health policy|work=myAJC|publisher=The Atlanta Journal-Constitution|date=December 3, 2016|accessdate=October 6, 2017}}</ref> He was replaced as majority leader by Bill Stephens on June 17, 2003.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://go.galegroup.com/ps/retrieve.do?tabID=T004&resultListType=RESULT_LIST&searchResultsType=SingleTab&searchType=BasicSearchForm&currentPosition=2&docId=GALE%7CA103877475&docType=Article&sort=DA-ASC-SORT&contentSegment=&prodId=STND&contentSet=GALE%7CA103877475&searchId=R6&userGroupName=fairfax_main&inPS=true|author=Rhonda Cook|title=Ethics Probe Targets State Senator|work=The Atlanta Journal-Constitution|date=June 21, 2003|accessdate=October 9, 2017}} {{subscription required|via=Infotrac Newsstand}}</ref>\n\n==U.S. House of Representatives (2005\u20132017)==\n\n===Elections===\n;2004\n[[File:Tom Price original.jpg|thumb|right|upright|Congressman Price in 2005]]\nIn late April 2003, Price formally announced his candidacy for [[Georgia's 6th congressional district]] in the [[United States House of Representatives]].<ref>{{cite news|title=Senate majority leader announces bid for 6th seat Tom Price to seek Isakson's spot|work=[[Marietta Daily Journal]]|date=April 29, 2003}}</ref><ref name=\"Race to Replace\">{{cite web|url=http://go.galegroup.com/ps/retrieve.do?tabID=T004&resultListType=RESULT_LIST&searchResultsType=SingleTab&searchType=AdvancedSearchForm&currentPosition=6&docId=GALE%7CA101029116&docType=Brief+article&sort=Relevance&contentSegment=&prodId=STND&contentSet=GALE%7CA101029116&searchId=R4&userGroupName=fairfax_main&inPS=true|author=James Salzer|title=Race to replace Isakson grows \\ Senate GOP leader seeks U.S. House seat|work=The Atlanta Journal-Constitution|date=April 29, 2003|accessdate=October 6, 2017}} {{subscription required|via=Infotrac Newsstand}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=GOP leader Tom Price running for Congress|work=[[Athens Banner-Herald]]|date=October 6, 2017}}</ref> The seat was being vacated by Republican [[Johnny Isakson]], who had decided to pursue an opening in the U.S. Senate.<ref name=\"Barr Bid\">{{cite web|url=https://www.highbeam.com/doc/1G1-97844696.html|author=James G. Lakely|title=Barr to Make Bid for Vacant Georgia Seat|work=[[The Washington Times]]|date=February 19, 2003|accessdate=October 6, 2017}} {{subscription required|via=HighBeam}}</ref> [[Bob Barr]], a former U.S. Congressman, was considered an early frontrunner in the race to replace Isakson, but Barr withdrew his candidacy for personal reasons, shortly before Price entered the race.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://go.galegroup.com/ps/retrieve.do?tabID=T004&resultListType=RESULT_LIST&searchResultsType=SingleTab&searchType=AdvancedSearchForm&currentPosition=3&docId=GALE%7CA96731575&docType=Article&sort=DA-ASC-SORT&contentSegment=&prodId=STND&contentSet=GALE%7CA96731575&searchId=R6&userGroupName=fairfax_main&inPS=true|author=Jennifer Brett|title=Isakson Seat Draws Interest \\ Name Recognition Seen as Key|work=The Atlanta Journal-Constitution|date=January 23, 2003|accessdate=October 6, 2017}} {{subscription required|via=Infotrac Newsstand}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.highbeam.com/doc/1G1-100554011.html|author=Greg Pierce|title=Barr Ends Candidacy|work=The Washington Times|date=April 24, 2003|accessdate=October 6, 2017}} {{subscription required|via=HighBeam}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.highbeam.com/doc/1P2-269966.html|author=Brian Faler|title=Barr Gives Up Bid to Return to House|work=The Washington Post|date=April 24, 2003|accessdate=October 6, 2017}} {{subscription required|via=HighBeam}}</ref> Price went onto run against two fellow state senators, Chuck Clay and Robert Lamutt, as well as two state representatives, Roger Hines and Mark Burkhalter.<ref name=\"Filing Starts\">{{cite web|url=http://go.galegroup.com/ps/retrieve.do?tabID=T004&resultListType=RESULT_LIST&searchResultsType=SingleTab&searchType=AdvancedSearchForm&currentPosition=26&docId=GALE%7CA115670060&docType=Article&sort=DA-ASC-SORT&contentSegment=&prodId=STND&contentSet=GALE%7CA115670060&searchId=R6&userGroupName=fairfax_main&inPS=true|author=Don Plummer|title=Election 2004: Filing Starts Monday \\ Offices High and Low on '04 Ballot|work=The Atlanta Journal-Constitution|date=April 22, 2004|accessdate=October 6, 2017}} {{subscription needed|via=Infotrac Newsstand}}</ref><ref name=\"Democrats Spice\">{{cite web|url=http://go.galegroup.com/ps/retrieve.do?tabID=T004&resultListType=RESULT_LIST&searchResultsType=SingleTab&searchType=AdvancedSearchForm&currentPosition=34&docId=GALE%7CA116265081&docType=Article&sort=DA-ASC-SORT&contentSegment=&prodId=STND&contentSet=GALE%7CA116265081&searchId=R6&userGroupName=fairfax_main&inPS=true|author=Richard Whitt|title=Election 2004: Tight Races, Democrats Spice Up Primary|work=The Atlanta Journal-Constitution|date=May 6, 2004|accessdate=October 6, 2017}} {{subscription required|via=Infotrac Newsstand}}</ref> Also taking part in the race was John McCallum, a former aide to [[U.S. House Speaker]] [[Newt Gingrich]].<ref name=\"Hopefuls\">{{cite web|url=http://go.galegroup.com/ps/retrieve.do?tabID=T004&resultListType=RESULT_LIST&searchResultsType=SingleTab&searchType=AdvancedSearchForm&currentPosition=7&docId=GALE%7CA101244747&docType=Article&sort=Relevance&contentSegment=&prodId=STND&contentSet=GALE%7CA101244747&searchId=R4&userGroupName=fairfax_main&inPS=true|author=Tom Baxter|title=Herd of Hopefuls Run for Dream 6th Seat|work=The Atlanta Journal-Constitution|date=May 6, 2003|accessdate=October 6, 2017}} {{subscription required|via=Infotrac Newsstand}}</ref><ref name=\"Clay in Race\">{{cite web|url=http://go.galegroup.com/ps/retrieve.do?tabID=T004&resultListType=RESULT_LIST&searchResultsType=SingleTab&searchType=AdvancedSearchForm&currentPosition=17&docId=GALE%7CA101839473&docType=Brief+article&sort=DA-ASC-SORT&contentSegment=&prodId=STND&contentSet=GALE%7CA101839473&searchId=R6&userGroupName=fairfax_main&inPS=true|author=Jennifer Brett|title=Clay in Race for Isakson House Seat|work=The Atlanta Journal-Constitution|date=May 16, 2003|accessdate=October 6, 2017}} {{subscription required|via=Infotrac Newsstand}}</ref>\n\nAt the time, Georgia's 6th Congressional district included parts of [[Fulton County, Georgia|Fulton]], [[Cherokee County, Georgia|Cherokee]], and [[Cobb County, Georgia|Cobb]] counties.<ref name=\"Race to Replace\"/><ref name=\"Clay in Race\"/> The district lines had been drawn so as to heavily favor Republicans - ''[[The Atlanta Journal-Constitution]]'' called the district a \"honey pot\" for the party and suggested that whoever won that year's primary would likely retain the seat \"into the next decade\".<ref name=\"Hopefuls\"/> Isakson had won the previous election with eighty percent of the vote,<ref name=\"Barr Bid\"/> and no Democrat entered the race to replace him.<ref name=\"Filing Starts\"/><ref name=\"Democrats Spice\"/><ref name=\"Clay in Race\"/>\n\nFollowing Barr's withdrawal from the race, Lamutt, a millionaire [[venture capitalist]] who self-financed much of his own campaign, was generally considered to be the new frontrunner;<ref name=\"myAJC\"/> although ''The Atlanta Journal-Constitution'' suggested that Clay, who had previously run an unsuccessful campaign to be [[Lieutenant Governor of Georgia|Lieutenant Governor of the state]], likely had the most name recognition of the remaining candidates.<ref name=\"Hopefuls\"/> Clay had also served as Republican minority leader in the state legislature, several years before Price became the party's majority leader.<ref name=\"Macon 98\"/> Price's residence in Fulton County was seen as a disadvantage, because the 6th district had been exclusively represented by Cobb County residents since 1991.<ref name=\"myAJC\"/> All of Price's opponents on the final ballot lived in Cobb.<ref name=\"Mere Sliver\">{{cite web|url=http://go.galegroup.com/ps/retrieve.do?tabID=T004&resultListType=RESULT_LIST&searchResultsType=SingleTab&searchType=BasicSearchForm&currentPosition=1&docId=GALE%7CA121153152&docType=Article&sort=Relevance&contentSegment=&prodId=STND&contentSet=GALE%7CA121153152&searchId=R3&userGroupName=fairfax_main&inPS=true|author=Clint Williams|title=6th Congressional District: County Has Mere Sliver of Representation|work=The Atlanta Journal-Constitution|date=July 15, 2004|accessdate=October 7, 2017}} {{subscription required|via=Infotrac Newsstand}}</ref><ref name=\"Shape Up\">{{cite web|url=http://go.galegroup.com/ps/retrieve.do?tabID=T004&resultListType=RESULT_LIST&searchResultsType=SingleTab&searchType=BasicSearchForm&currentPosition=1&docId=GALE%7CA121154080&docType=Article&sort=Relevance&contentSegment=&prodId=STND&contentSet=GALE%7CA121154080&searchId=R4&userGroupName=fairfax_main&inPS=true|author=James Salzer|title=Election 2004: The Primary: Congressional Contests: House Races Shape Up as Runoffs \\ Scott Notches Solid Win in 13th District|work=The Atlanta Journal-Constitution|date=July 21, 2004|accessdate=October 7, 2017}} {{subscription required|via=Infotrac Newsstand}}</ref> Price considered relocating, in order to improve his chances in the race, but he ultimately decided against this.<ref name=\"myAJC\"/><ref name=\"Foes Spar\">{{cite web|url=http://go.galegroup.com/ps/retrieve.do?tabID=T004&resultListType=RESULT_LIST&searchResultsType=SingleTab&searchType=BasicSearchForm&currentPosition=1&docId=GALE%7CA121158663&docType=Brief+article&sort=Relevance&contentSegment=&prodId=STND&contentSet=GALE%7CA121158663&searchId=R5&userGroupName=fairfax_main&inPS=true|author=Richard Whitt|title=Election 2004: 6th District Foes Spar on  Tax Votes|work=The Atlanta Journal-Constitution|date=August 2, 2004|accessdate=October 9, 2017}} {{subscription required|via=Infotrac Newsstand}}</ref>\n\nDespite this handicap, Price had out-raised his opponents by late July,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://go.galegroup.com/ps/retrieve.do?tabID=T004&resultListType=RESULT_LIST&searchResultsType=SingleTab&searchType=AdvancedSearchForm&currentPosition=19&docId=GALE%7CA105762639&docType=Article&sort=DA-ASC-SORT&contentSegment=&prodId=STND&contentSet=GALE%7CA105762639&searchId=R6&userGroupName=fairfax_main&inPS=true|author=Tom Baxter|title=Campaigns Covet 'Bush-Type' Contributors|work=The Atlanta Journal-Constitution|date=July 24, 2003|accessdate=October 7, 2017}} {{subscription required|via=Infotrac Newsstand}}</ref> and although he was briefly overtaken by Clay,<ref name=\"Grab Money\">{{cite web|url=http://go.galegroup.com/ps/retrieve.do?tabID=T004&resultListType=RESULT_LIST&searchResultsType=SingleTab&searchType=AdvancedSearchForm&currentPosition=22&docId=GALE%7CA112922676&docType=Brief+article&sort=DA-ASC-SORT&contentSegment=&prodId=STND&contentSet=GALE%7CA112922676&searchId=R6&userGroupName=fairfax_main&inPS=true|author1=Tom Baxter|author2=Jim Galloway|title=Legislature 2004: Georgians Grab Money|work=The Atlanta Journal-Constitution|date=February 5, 2004|accessdate=October 7, 2017}} {{subscription required|via=Infotrac Newsstand}}</ref> he reclaimed his top position in the 6th district race within a few months.<ref name=\"At Least $1 Million\">{{cite web|url=http://go.galegroup.com/ps/retrieve.do?tabID=T004&resultListType=RESULT_LIST&searchResultsType=SingleTab&searchType=AdvancedSearchForm&currentPosition=27&docId=GALE%7CA116005071&docType=Article&sort=DA-ASC-SORT&contentSegment=&prodId=STND&contentSet=GALE%7CA116005071&searchId=R6&userGroupName=fairfax_main&inPS=true|author=Sonji Jacobs|title=GOP Hopefuls Lead Race for Funds \\ 5 Running for Congress Raise at Least $1 Million|work=The Atlanta Journal-Constitution|date=April 29, 2004|accessdate=October 7, 2017}} {{subscription required|via=Infotrac Newsstand}}</ref> In February 2004, it was reported that Clay and Price were the two highest-funded candidates in that year's Congressional races, nationwide.<ref name=\"Grab Money\"/> Federal election law put a limit of $2,000 on individual contributions to the campaigns, but Lamutt activated a clause that raised this limit to $6,000 for his opponents, when he loaned $600,000 to his own campaign.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://go.galegroup.com/ps/retrieve.do?tabID=T004&resultListType=RESULT_LIST&searchResultsType=SingleTab&searchType=AdvancedSearchForm&currentPosition=20&docId=GALE%7CA110935431&docType=Brief+article&sort=DA-ASC-SORT&contentSegment=&prodId=STND&contentSet=GALE%7CA110935431&searchId=R6&userGroupName=fairfax_main&inPS=true|author=Rhonda Cook|title=Cash Spigot Opened in Race for 6th|work=The Atlanta Journal-Constitution|date=December 5, 2003|accessdate=October 7, 2017}} {{subscription required|via=Infotrac Newsstand}}</ref> Lamutt would eventually increase this loan to $1.5 million,<ref name=\"myAJC\"/> while Clay loaned at least $500,000 to his own campaign. In late April 2004, it was reported that Price had put a loan of $200,000 into the race - despite this disparity in self-funding, Price had received contributions from a significantly higher number of donors than his opponents. At least $300,000 of Price's campaign funds came from the [[health care industry]].<ref name=\"At Least $1 Million\"/>\n\nIn the final week of the election, several polls had Price ahead.<ref name=\"Take the Stage\">{{cite web|url=http://go.galegroup.com/ps/retrieve.do?tabID=T004&resultListType=RESULT_LIST&searchResultsType=SingleTab&searchType=BasicSearchForm&currentPosition=1&docId=GALE%7CA121153399&docType=Article&sort=Relevance&contentSegment=&prodId=STND&contentSet=GALE%7CA121153399&searchId=R6&userGroupName=fairfax_main&inPS=true|author=Richard Whitt|title=6th District Candidates Take the Stage|work=The Atlanta Journal-Constitution|date=July 12, 2004|accessdate=October 7, 2017}} {{subscription required|via=Infotrac Newsstand}}</ref><ref name=\"Tuesday\">{{cite web|url=http://go.galegroup.com/ps/retrieve.do?tabID=T004&resultListType=RESULT_LIST&searchResultsType=SingleTab&searchType=BasicSearchForm&currentPosition=1&docId=GALE%7CA121153533&docType=Article&sort=Relevance&contentSegment=&prodId=STND&contentSet=GALE%7CA121153533&searchId=R7&userGroupName=fairfax_main&inPS=true|author1=Nancy Badertscher|author2=Corey Dade|author3=Doug Nurse|author4=Brenden Sager|author5=Pete Scott|author6=Eric Sturgis|title=Election 2004: What's Up for Grabs on Tuesday|work=The Atlanta Journal-Constitution|date=July 18, 2004|accessdate=October 7, 2017}} {{subscription required|via=Infotrac Newsstand}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://go.galegroup.com/ps/retrieve.do?tabID=T004&resultListType=RESULT_LIST&searchResultsType=SingleTab&searchType=BasicSearchForm&currentPosition=1&docId=GALE%7CA121153658&docType=Article&sort=Relevance&contentSegment=&prodId=STND&contentSet=GALE%7CA121153658&searchId=R8&userGroupName=fairfax_main&inPS=true|author1=Jim Galloway|author2=Richard Whitt|title=Finish Line Nears as Candidates Hit Streets|work=The Atlanta Journal-Constitution|date=July 19, 2004|accessdate=October 7, 2017}} {{subscription required|via=Infotrac Newsstand}}</ref> ''The Atlanta Journal-Constitution'' endorsed Clay over Price and the others, arguing that there was \"little difference among the contestants on the issues\", but that Clay had exhibited the greatest skill as a negotiator, while in the state legislature.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://go.galegroup.com/ps/retrieve.do?tabID=T004&resultListType=RESULT_LIST&searchResultsType=SingleTab&searchType=BasicSearchForm&currentPosition=1&docId=GALE%7CA121152991&docType=Article&sort=Relevance&contentSegment=&prodId=STND&contentSet=GALE%7CA121152991&searchId=R9&userGroupName=fairfax_main&inPS=true|author=''The Atlanta Journal-Constitution'' staff|title=Our Opinions: Few Signs of Suspense \\ A Dearth of Challengers for Incumbents Limits Georgia Voters' Options in Races for U.S. House|work=The Atlanta Journal-Constitution|date=July 16, 2004|accessdate=October 8, 2017}} {{subscription required|via=Infotrac Newsstand}}</ref> Burkhalter and McCallum were not on the final ballot.<ref name=\"Mere Sliver\"/><ref name=\"Tuesday\"/><ref name=\"Vote Absentee\">{{cite web|url=http://go.galegroup.com/ps/retrieve.do?tabID=T004&resultListType=RESULT_LIST&searchResultsType=SingleTab&searchType=BasicSearchForm&currentPosition=1&docId=GALE%7CA121288087&docType=Article&sort=Relevance&contentSegment=&prodId=STND&contentSet=GALE%7CA121288087&searchId=R10&userGroupName=fairfax_main&inPS=true|author=''The Atlanta Journal-Constitution'' staff|title=Election 2004: Vote Absentee or Early|work=The Atlanta Journal-Constitution|date=July 1, 2004|accessdate=October 7, 2017}} {{subscription required|via=Infotrac Newsstand}}</ref> On July 11, 2004, a televised debate was held between the remaining candidates.<ref name=\"Take the Stage\"/><ref>{{cite web|url=http://go.galegroup.com/ps/retrieve.do?tabID=T004&resultListType=RESULT_LIST&searchResultsType=SingleTab&searchType=AdvancedSearchForm&currentPosition=2&docId=GALE%7CA121288527&docType=Brief+article&sort=Relevance&contentSegment=&prodId=STND&contentSet=GALE%7CA121288527&searchId=R14&userGroupName=fairfax_main&inPS=true|author=''The Atlanta Journal-Constitution'' staff|title=Election 2004|work=The Atlanta Journal-Constitution|date=July 4, 2004|accessdate=October 7, 2017}} {{subscription required|via=Infotrac Newsstand}}</ref> The election was then held on July 20.<ref name=\"Vote Absentee\"/> While early voting results showed Lamutt in the lead,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://go.galegroup.com/ps/retrieve.do?tabID=T004&resultListType=RESULT_LIST&searchResultsType=SingleTab&searchType=BasicSearchForm&currentPosition=1&docId=GALE%7CA121154041&docType=Article&sort=Relevance&contentSegment=&prodId=STND&contentSet=GALE%7CA121154041&searchId=R16&userGroupName=fairfax_main&inPS=true|author=Jim Galloway|title=Election 2004: Sears Fends Off GOP Attack \\ Isakson Leads Race for U.S. Senate Seat; McKinney on Track|work=The Atlanta Journal-Constitution|date=July 21, 2004|accessdate=October 8, 2017}} {{subscription required|via=Infotrac Newsstand}}</ref> Price overtook him by the end of the night<ref name=\"Shape Up\"/> and finished in first with 35% of the vote. Lamutt came in second, earning 28% of the vote, and Clay took third with 21% of the vote.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://go.galegroup.com/ps/retrieve.do?tabID=T004&resultListType=RESULT_LIST&searchResultsType=SingleTab&searchType=AdvancedSearchForm&currentPosition=55&docId=GALE%7CA121154522&docType=Article&sort=DA-ASC-SORT&contentSegment=&prodId=STND&contentSet=GALE%7CA121154522&searchId=R2&userGroupName=fairfax_main&inPS=true|author=''The Atlanta Journal-Constitution'' staff|title=Election 2004: Primary Results|work=The Atlanta Journal-Constitution|date=July 22, 2004|accessdate=October 8, 2017}} {{subscription required|via=Infotrac Newsstand}}</ref> Because Price failed to earn over 50% of the vote, a run-off election between him and Lamutt was scheduled for August 10.<ref name=\"Shape Up\"/><ref>{{cite web|url=http://go.galegroup.com/ps/retrieve.do?tabID=T004&resultListType=RESULT_LIST&searchResultsType=SingleTab&searchType=AdvancedSearchForm&currentPosition=50&docId=GALE%7CA121154090&docType=Article&sort=DA-ASC-SORT&contentSegment=&prodId=STND&contentSet=GALE%7CA121154090&searchId=R2&userGroupName=fairfax_main&inPS=true&authCount=1&u=fairfax_main|author=James Salzer|title=Election 2004: The Primary: Congressional Contests: House Races Advance to Runoffs \\ Scott Notches Solid Win in 13th District|work=The Atlanta Journal-Constitution|date=July 21, 2004|accessdate=October 8, 2017}} {{subscription required|via=Infotrac Newsstand}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://go.galegroup.com/ps/retrieve.do?tabID=T004&resultListType=RESULT_LIST&searchResultsType=SingleTab&searchType=AdvancedSearchForm&currentPosition=51&docId=GALE%7CA121154096&docType=Article&sort=DA-ASC-SORT&contentSegment=&prodId=STND&contentSet=GALE%7CA121154096&searchId=R2&userGroupName=fairfax_main&inPS=true|author=Jim Galloway|title=Election 2004: McKinney Storms to Lead; Isakson Wins Senate Bid \\ Justice Sears Beats Challenger Backed by Governor, GOP|work=The Atlanta Journal-Constitution|date=July 21, 2004|accessdate=October 8, 2017}} {{subscription required|via=Infotrac Newsstand}}</ref>\n\n''The Atlanta Journal-Constitution'' proceeded to endorse Price in the run-off election, arguing that he had demonstrated strong leadership abilities in the state senate, during \"difficult budget years\".<ref>{{cite web|url=http://go.galegroup.com/ps/retrieve.do?tabID=T004&resultListType=RESULT_LIST&searchResultsType=SingleTab&searchType=AdvancedSearchForm&currentPosition=2&docId=GALE%7CA121287222&docType=Article&sort=Relevance&contentSegment=&prodId=STND&contentSet=GALE%7CA121287222&searchId=R7&userGroupName=fairfax_main&inPS=true|author=''The Atlanta Journal-Constitution'' staff|title=Our Opinion: Editorial: This Runoff Holds Primary Importance \\ From a Fulton Sheriff to Key State Contests, Voters on Tuesday Must Revisit Races Not Settled in July|work=The Atlanta Journal-Constitution|date=August 8, 2004|accessdate=October 9, 2017}} {{subscription required|via=Infotrac Newsstand}}</ref> Lamutt was generally favored to win though, based on the assumption that he would consolidate the vote in Cobb County.<ref name=\"Foes Spar\"/><ref>{{cite web|url=http://go.galegroup.com/ps/retrieve.do?tabID=T004&resultListType=RESULT_LIST&searchResultsType=SingleTab&searchType=AdvancedSearchForm&currentPosition=58&docId=GALE%7CA121154571&docType=Article&sort=DA-ASC-SORT&contentSegment=&prodId=STND&contentSet=GALE%7CA121154571&searchId=R1&userGroupName=fairfax_main&inPS=true|author=Jim Wooten|title=Thinking Right: Moore Cult, Election|work=The Atlanta Journal-Constitution|date=July 23, 2004|accessdate=October 9, 2017}} {{subscription required|via=Infotrac Newsstand}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://go.galegroup.com/ps/retrieve.do?tabID=T004&resultListType=RESULT_LIST&searchResultsType=SingleTab&searchType=AdvancedSearchForm&currentPosition=59&docId=GALE%7CA440236909&docType=Article&sort=DA-ASC-SORT&contentSegment=&prodId=STND&contentSet=GALE%7CA440236909&searchId=R1&userGroupName=fairfax_main&inPS=true|author=''United Press International'' staff|title=UPI Political Briefs|work=[[United Press International]]|date=July 26, 2004|accessdate=October 9, 2017}} {{subscription required|via=Infotrac Newsstand}}</ref> A televised debate between Price and Lamutt was held on August 1,<ref name=\"Foes Spar\"/><ref>{{cite web|url=http://go.galegroup.com/ps/retrieve.do?tabID=T004&resultListType=RESULT_LIST&searchResultsType=SingleTab&searchType=AdvancedSearchForm&currentPosition=63&docId=GALE%7CA121158545&docType=Article&sort=DA-ASC-SORT&contentSegment=&prodId=STND&contentSet=GALE%7CA121158545&searchId=R1&userGroupName=fairfax_main&inPS=true|author1=Eric Stirgus|author2=Richard Whitt|title=Election 2004: Runoff to Test Voters' Mettle \\ Primary-Worn Candidates Spend Final Days Urging Core Supporters to Return to Polls|work=The Atlanta Journal-Constitution|date=August 1, 2004|accessdate=October 9, 2017}} {{subscription required|via=Infotrac Newsstand}}</ref> and early voting began the following day - the first time in Georgia state history that early voting was allowed in a runoff election.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://go.galegroup.com/ps/retrieve.do?tabID=T004&resultListType=RESULT_LIST&searchResultsType=SingleTab&searchType=AdvancedSearchForm&currentPosition=64&docId=GALE%7CA121158636&docType=Brief+article&sort=DA-ASC-SORT&contentSegment=&prodId=STND&contentSet=GALE%7CA121158636&searchId=R1&userGroupName=fairfax_main&inPS=true|author=Brenden Sager|title=Election 2004: Early Voting Kicks Off in Runoffs|work=The Atlanta Journal-Constitution|date=August 2, 2004|accessdate=October 9, 2017}} {{subscription required|via=Infotrac Newsstand}}</ref> Price upset expectations by winning 54% of the vote - carrying about 80% in Fulton County and about 40% in Cobb County.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://go.galegroup.com/ps/retrieve.do?tabID=T004&resultListType=RESULT_LIST&searchResultsType=SingleTab&searchType=AdvancedSearchForm&currentPosition=79&docId=GALE%7CA121422546&docType=Article&sort=DA-ASC-SORT&contentSegment=&prodId=STND&contentSet=GALE%7CA121422546&searchId=R1&userGroupName=fairfax_main&inPS=true|author1=Aixa Pascual|author2=Richard Whitt|title=Election 2004: The Runoffs: 6th District: Fulton Gives Price Edge|work=The Atlanta Journal-Constitution|date=August 11, 2004|accessdate=October 9, 2017}} {{subscription required|via=Infotrac Newsstand}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://go.galegroup.com/ps/retrieve.do?tabID=T004&resultListType=RESULT_LIST&searchResultsType=SingleTab&searchType=AdvancedSearchForm&currentPosition=80&docId=GALE%7CA121422549&docType=Article&sort=DA-ASC-SORT&contentSegment=&prodId=STND&contentSet=GALE%7CA121422549&searchId=R1&userGroupName=fairfax_main&inPS=true|author=Jim Tharpe|title=Election 2004: Majette Makes History \\ Westmoreland, Price Win Bids for Congress|work=The Atlanta Journal-Constitution|date=August 11, 2004|accessdate=October 9, 2017}} {{subscription required|via=Infotrac Newsstand}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://go.galegroup.com/ps/retrieve.do?tabID=T004&resultListType=RESULT_LIST&searchResultsType=SingleTab&searchType=AdvancedSearchForm&currentPosition=81&docId=GALE%7CA121422550&docType=Brief+article&sort=DA-ASC-SORT&contentSegment=&prodId=STND&contentSet=GALE%7CA121422550&searchId=R1&userGroupName=fairfax_main&inPS=true|author=''The Atlanta Journal-Constitution'' staff|title=Election 2004: Runoff Results|work=The Atlanta Journal-Constitution|date=August 11, 2004|accessdate=October 9, 2017}} {{subscription required|via=Infotrac Newsstand}}</ref> Price then won the general election unopposed.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.ourcampaigns.com/RaceDetail.html?RaceID=4101|title= GA \u2013 District 06 Race \u2013 Nov 02, 2004|publisher=Our Campaigns|accessdate=November 19, 2016}}</ref><ref>{{Cite journal|last=Jeff Trandahlm, Clerk of the House of Representatives|first=|year=2004|title=Statistics of the Presidential and Congressional Election of November 2, 2004|url=http://clerk.house.gov/member_info/electionInfo/2004election.pdf|journal=|volume=|pages=16|via=}}</ref>\n\n;2006\nGeorgia's 6th Congressional district was redrawn in 2005, to include all of Cherokee County.<ref name=\"Konop\">{{cite web|url=http://go.galegroup.com/ps/retrieve.do?tabID=T004&resultListType=RESULT_LIST&searchResultsType=SingleTab&searchType=BasicSearchForm&currentPosition=7&docId=GALE%7CA143869913&docType=Brief+article&sort=DA-ASC-SORT&contentSegment=&prodId=STND&contentSet=GALE%7CA143869913&searchId=R7&userGroupName=fairfax_main&inPS=true|author=Clint Williams|title=Politics already back in season; Candidates will qualify in April|work=The Atlanta Journal-Constitution|date=March 30, 2006|accessdate=October 9, 2017}} {{subscription required|via=Infotrac Newsstand}}</ref> That Fall, John Konop, a businessman from Cherokee, announced that he would challenge Price in the Republican primary.<ref name=\"Konop\"/><ref>{{cite web|url=http://go.galegroup.com/ps/retrieve.do?tabID=T004&resultListType=RESULT_LIST&searchResultsType=SingleTab&searchType=BasicSearchForm&currentPosition=3&docId=GALE%7CA141541582&docType=Article&sort=DA-ASC-SORT&contentSegment=&prodId=STND&contentSet=GALE%7CA141541582&searchId=R7&userGroupName=fairfax_main&inPS=true|author=Jim Tharpe|title=Forum Previews Debate on Illegals|work=The Atlanta Journal-Constitution|date=February 1, 2006|accessdate=October 9, 2017}} {{subscription required|via=Infotrac Newsstand}}</ref><ref name=\"Cherokee\">{{cite web|url=http://go.galegroup.com/ps/retrieve.do?tabID=T004&resultListType=RESULT_LIST&searchResultsType=SingleTab&searchType=BasicSearchForm&currentPosition=4&docId=GALE%7CA141857421&docType=Article&sort=DA-ASC-SORT&contentSegment=&prodId=STND&contentSet=GALE%7CA141857421&searchId=R7&userGroupName=fairfax_main&inPS=true|author=Clint Williams|title=Cherokee Reporter's Notebook|work=The Atlanta Journal-Constitution|date=February 9, 2006|accessdate=October 9, 2017}} {{subscription required|via=Infotrac Newsstand}}</ref> Konop ran to the right of Price on immigration policy and criticized Price's support for the [[Central American Free Trade Agreement]]. He also argued that Price's support for transportation and energy bills would increase the federal deficit. Price defended these bills, arguing that the former would return more tax-payer money to Georgia and that the latter could potentially help the United States achieve [[energy independence]].<ref name=\"Energy, Finances\">{{cite web|url=http://go.galegroup.com/ps/retrieve.do?tabID=T004&resultListType=RESULT_LIST&searchResultsType=SingleTab&searchType=BasicSearchForm&currentPosition=16&docId=GALE%7CA147959421&docType=Brief+article&sort=DA-ASC-SORT&contentSegment=&prodId=STND&contentSet=GALE%7CA147959421&searchId=R7&userGroupName=fairfax_main&inPS=true|author=Richard Whitt|title=Energy, Finances Focus of Debate: GOP Hopefuls Urge Less Use of Foreign Oil|work=The Atlanta Journal-Constitution|date=July 8, 2006|accessdate=October 10, 2017}} {{subscription required|via=Infotrac Newsstand}}</ref><ref name=\"Long Shot\">{{cite web|url=http://go.galegroup.com/ps/retrieve.do?tabID=T004&resultListType=RESULT_LIST&searchResultsType=SingleTab&searchType=BasicSearchForm&currentPosition=17&docId=GALE%7CA148054445&docType=Article&sort=DA-ASC-SORT&contentSegment=&prodId=STND&contentSet=GALE%7CA148054445&searchId=R7&userGroupName=fairfax_main&inPS=true|author=Richard Whitt|title=Election 2006 - The Primaries: Long Shot Konop Faces Rep. Price|work=The Atlanta Journal-Constitution|date=July 11, 2006|accessdate=October 10, 2017}} {{subscription required|via=Infotrac Newsstand}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://go.galegroup.com/ps/retrieve.do?tabID=T004&resultListType=RESULT_LIST&searchResultsType=SingleTab&searchType=AdvancedSearchForm&currentPosition=22&docId=GALE%7CA148186945&docType=Article&sort=DA-ASC-SORT&contentSegment=&prodId=STND&contentSet=GALE%7CA148186945&searchId=R1&userGroupName=fairfax_main&inPS=true|author=''The Atlanta Journal-Constitution'' staff|title=Cobb Voters Guide|work=The Atlanta Journal-Constitution|date=July 13, 2006|accessdate=October 10, 2017}} {{subscription required|via=Infotrac Newsstand}}</ref> Price raised $1.5 million throughout the primary campaign, while Konop merely raised around $50,000.<ref name=\"Long Shot\"/> ''The Atlanta Journal-Constitution'' endorsed Price in the primary election, suggesting that Price could play an important role in shaping future health care legislation.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://go.galegroup.com/ps/retrieve.do?tabID=T004&resultListType=RESULT_LIST&searchResultsType=SingleTab&searchType=AdvancedSearchForm&currentPosition=23&docId=GALE%7CA148186862&docType=Article&sort=DA-ASC-SORT&contentSegment=&prodId=STND&contentSet=GALE%7CA148186862&searchId=R1&userGroupName=fairfax_main&inPS=true|author=Mike King|title=Our Opinions: Primary Endorsements: Congressional Race: Just Say 'No' to McKinney, 'Yes' to Others|work=The Atlanta Journal-Constitution|date=July 14, 2006|accessdate=October 10, 2017}} {{subscription required|via=Infotrac Newsstand}}</ref> A televised debate between the candidates was held on July 7, 2006, and the election was then held on July 18.<ref name=\"Energy, Finances\"/> Price defeated Konop, 82%\u201318%.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://go.galegroup.com/ps/retrieve.do?tabID=T004&resultListType=RESULT_LIST&searchResultsType=SingleTab&searchType=BasicSearchForm&currentPosition=26&docId=GALE%7CA148366900&docType=Article&sort=DA-ASC-SORT&contentSegment=&prodId=STND&contentSet=GALE%7CA148366900&searchId=R1&userGroupName=fairfax_main&inPS=true&authCount=1&u=fairfax_main|author1=Anna Varela|author2=Richard Whitt|title=Georgia Primary 2006: Congress: Easy Wins Likely for House Incumbents|work=The Atlanta Journal-Constitution|date=July 19, 2006|accessdate=October 10, 2017}} {{subscription required|via=Infotrac Newsstand}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://go.galegroup.com/ps/retrieve.do?tabID=T004&resultListType=RESULT_LIST&searchResultsType=SingleTab&searchType=BasicSearchForm&currentPosition=21&docId=GALE%7CA148416121&docType=Article&sort=DA-SORT&contentSegment=&prodId=STND&contentSet=GALE%7CA148416121&searchId=R3&userGroupName=fairfax_main&inPS=true|author=''The Atlanta Journal-Constitution'' staff|title=Georgia 2006: About the Results|work=The Atlanta Journal-Constitution|date=July 20, 2006|accessdate=October 10, 2017}} {{subscription required|via=Infotrac Newsstand}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ourcampaigns.com/RaceDetail.html?RaceID=311132|title=GA District 06- R Primary Race \u2013 Jul 18, 2006|publisher=Our Campaigns|accessdate=November 19, 2016}}</ref>\n\nPrice then faced a Democratic challenger in the general election - Steve Sinton, a media figure from Cobb County, who had co-founded the liberal [[talk radio]] news network [[Air America (radio network)|Air America]].<ref name=\"Cherokee\"/> Sinton argued that the Republican-controlled Congress had been irresponsible in its spending policies and oversight of the Iraq War. ''The Atlanta Journal-Constitution'' considered these to be valid concerns, but endorsed Price for re-election, arguing that he would better represent the conservative 6th district's constituents.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://go.galegroup.com/ps/retrieve.do?tabID=T004&resultListType=RESULT_LIST&searchResultsType=SingleTab&searchType=BasicSearchForm&currentPosition=25&docId=GALE%7CA153633661&docType=Article&sort=DA-ASC-SORT&contentSegment=&prodId=STND&contentSet=GALE%7CA153633661&searchId=R4&userGroupName=fairfax_main&inPS=true|author=''The Atlanta Journal-Constitution'' staff|title=Our Opinion: Endorsements: Nov. 7 Elections: Go with Incumbents, for Most Part: Oust Westmoreland, Norwood, but Retain Other House Members|work=The Atlanta Journal-Constitution|date=November 1, 2006|accessdate=October 10, 2017}} {{subscription required|via=Infotrac Newsstand}}</ref> In November, Price won re-election to a second term with 72% of the vote.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://go.galegroup.com/ps/retrieve.do?tabID=T004&resultListType=RESULT_LIST&searchResultsType=SingleTab&searchType=BasicSearchForm&currentPosition=36&docId=GALE%7CA154078554&docType=Article&sort=DA-ASC-SORT&contentSegment=&prodId=STND&contentSet=GALE%7CA154078554&searchId=R4&userGroupName=fairfax_main&inPS=true|author=''The Atlanta Journal-Constitution'' staff|title=Georgia Votes 2006: Results of Contested Races|work=The Atlanta Journal-Constitution|date=November 8, 2006|accessdate=October 10, 2017}} {{subscription required|via=Infotrac Newsstand}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ourcampaigns.com/RaceDetail.html?RaceID=206831|title=GA \u2013 District 06 Race \u2013 Nov 07, 2006|publisher=Our Campaigns|accessdate=November 19, 2016}}</ref>\n\n;2008\u20132014\nPrice was unopposed in the 2008 Republican primary.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://go.galegroup.com/ps/retrieve.do?tabID=T004&resultListType=RESULT_LIST&searchResultsType=SingleTab&searchType=AdvancedSearchForm&currentPosition=2&docId=GALE%7CA180918318&docType=Company+overview&sort=DA-ASC-SORT&contentSegment=&prodId=STND&contentSet=GALE%7CA180918318&searchId=R1&userGroupName=fairfax_main&inPS=true|author=''The Atlanta Journal-Constitution'' staff|title=2008 Voters Guide|work=The Atlanta Journal-Constitution|date=July 3, 2008|accessdate=October 10, 2017}} {{subscription required|via=Infotrac Newsstand}}</ref> He then ran against Democratic candidate Bill Jones, a retired [[air force]] [[Aircraft pilot|pilot]], in the general election.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://go.galegroup.com/ps/retrieve.do?tabID=T004&resultListType=RESULT_LIST&searchResultsType=SingleTab&searchType=AdvancedSearchForm&currentPosition=1&docId=GALE%7CA178571449&docType=Article&sort=DA-ASC-SORT&contentSegment=&prodId=STND&contentSet=GALE%7CA178571449&searchId=R1&userGroupName=fairfax_main&inPS=true|author=Ben Smith|title=Congress' Johnson draws no opponent: Filing ends: Situation in 4th district hasn't been seen for 52 years; in state assembly, candidate sign-ups nearly ensure Republicans will keep control|work=The Atlanta Journal-Constitution|date=May 3, 2008|accessdate=October 10, 2017}} {{subscription required|via=Infotrac Newsstand}}</ref> Jones was described by ''The Atlanta Journal-Constitution'' as a moderate.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://go.galegroup.com/ps/retrieve.do?tabID=T004&resultListType=RESULT_LIST&searchResultsType=SingleTab&searchType=AdvancedSearchForm&currentPosition=13&docId=GALE%7CA198323021&docType=Article&sort=DA-ASC-SORT&contentSegment=&prodId=STND&contentSet=GALE%7CA198323021&searchId=R1&userGroupName=fairfax_main&inPS=true|author1=Shaila Dewan|author2=Robbie Brown|title=A Psychologist Helps Repackage Democrats' Message|work=The Atlanta Journal-Constitution|date=October 30, 2008|accessdate=October 10, 2017}} {{subscription required|via=Infotrac Newsstand}}</ref> He cited Price's opposition to an expansion of the [[Children's Health Insurance Program]] as one of his primary reasons for entering the race.<ref name=\"Jones Healthcare\">{{cite web|url=http://go.galegroup.com/ps/retrieve.do?tabID=T004&resultListType=RESULT_LIST&searchResultsType=SingleTab&searchType=AdvancedSearchForm&currentPosition=9&docId=GALE%7CA184789504&docType=Article&sort=DA-ASC-SORT&contentSegment=&prodId=STND&contentSet=GALE%7CA184789504&searchId=R1&userGroupName=fairfax_main&inPS=true|author=Kevin Sack|title=Health Care Issue, Not Quite Hot, Remains Strong|work=[[The New York Times]]|date=September 12, 2008|accessdate=October 10, 2017}} {{subscription required|via=Infotrac Newsstand}}</ref> Jones managed to raise over $225,000 - more than any other Democratic challenger in Georgia's congressional elections that year.<ref name=\"Incumbents\">{{cite web|url=http://go.galegroup.com/ps/retrieve.do?tabID=T004&resultListType=RESULT_LIST&searchResultsType=SingleTab&searchType=AdvancedSearchForm&currentPosition=10&docId=GALE%7CA185294408&docType=Article&sort=DA-ASC-SORT&contentSegment=&prodId=STND&contentSet=GALE%7CA185294408&searchId=R1&userGroupName=fairfax_main&inPS=true|author=Ben Smith|title=11 Incumbents Heavily Favored|work=The Atlanta Journal-Constitution|date=September 19, 2008|accessdate=October 10, 2017}} {{subscription required|via=Infotrac Newsstand}}</ref> An easy victory for Price was still predicted though.<ref name=\"Jones Healthcare\"/><ref name=\"Incumbents\"/> A debate was scheduled for October 21, 2008, but Price was not in attendance, as Congress was in session at the time. Jones was still allowed to deliver remarks at the event.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://go.galegroup.com/ps/retrieve.do?tabID=T004&resultListType=RESULT_LIST&searchResultsType=SingleTab&searchType=AdvancedSearchForm&currentPosition=11&docId=GALE%7CA187564270&docType=Brief+article&sort=DA-ASC-SORT&contentSegment=&prodId=STND&contentSet=GALE%7CA187564270&searchId=R1&userGroupName=fairfax_main&inPS=true|author=Ben Smith|title=Community News: Incumbent Congressmen Fail to Show Up at Debates|work=The Atlanta Journal-Constitution|date=October 22, 2008|accessdate=October 10, 2017}} {{subscription required|via=Infotrac Newsstand}}</ref> Price carried a large margin of victory over Jones, earning 69% of the vote.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://go.galegroup.com/ps/retrieve.do?tabID=T004&resultListType=RESULT_LIST&searchResultsType=SingleTab&searchType=AdvancedSearchForm&currentPosition=14&docId=GALE%7CA188435809&docType=Article&sort=DA-ASC-SORT&contentSegment=&prodId=STND&contentSet=GALE%7CA188435809&searchId=R1&userGroupName=fairfax_main&inPS=true|author=Ben Smith|title=Election 2008: The Voters Speak: Georgia House: Incumbents Score 7 Republicans, 3 Democrats: Marshall Has 10 Percentage-Point Lead Over Goddard in 8th District Race|work=The Atlanta Journal-Constitution|date=November 5, 2008|accessdate=October 10, 2017}} {{subscription required|via=Infotrac Newsstand}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://go.galegroup.com/ps/retrieve.do?tabID=T004&resultListType=RESULT_LIST&searchResultsType=SingleTab&searchType=AdvancedSearchForm&currentPosition=20&docId=GALE%7CA188473022&docType=Statistical+table&sort=DA-ASC-SORT&contentSegment=&prodId=STND&contentSet=GALE%7CA188473022&searchId=R1&userGroupName=fairfax_main&inPS=true|author=''The New York Times'' staff|title=The Races for the House|work=The New York Times|date=November 6, 2008|accessdate=October 10, 2017}} {{subscription required|via=Infotrac Newsstand}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ourcampaigns.com/RaceDetail.html?RaceID=387947|title=GA \u2013 District 06 Race \u2013 Nov 04, 2008|publisher=Our Campaigns|accessdate=November 19, 2016}}</ref>\n\nIn 2010, Price was unopposed in both the primary and the general election.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://go.galegroup.com/ps/retrieve.do?tabID=T004&resultListType=RESULT_LIST&searchResultsType=SingleTab&searchType=AdvancedSearchForm&currentPosition=22&docId=GALE%7CA225321987&docType=Article&sort=DA-ASC-SORT&contentSegment=&prodId=STND&contentSet=GALE%7CA225321987&searchId=R1&userGroupName=fairfax_main&inPS=true|author=Aaron Gould Sheinin|title=14 File to Run for Governor: State's U.S. Senate Race Draws Three. Some Legislative, Congressional Seats Uncontested|work=The Atlanta Journal-Constitution|date=May 1, 2010|accessdate=October 11, 2017}} {{subscription required|via=Infotrac Newsstand}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://go.galegroup.com/ps/retrieve.do?tabID=T004&resultListType=RESULT_LIST&searchResultsType=SingleTab&searchType=AdvancedSearchForm&currentPosition=23&docId=GALE%7CA231927858&docType=Article&sort=DA-ASC-SORT&contentSegment=&prodId=STND&contentSet=GALE%7CA231927858&searchId=R1&userGroupName=fairfax_main&inPS=true|author=''UPI NewsTrack'' staff|title=Georgia: Dems, GOP Eye Each Other's Seats|work=UPI NewsTrack|date=July 18, 2010|accessdate=October 11, 2017}} {{subscription required|via=Infotrac Newsstand}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ourcampaigns.com/RaceDetail.html?RaceID=488686|title=GA \u2013 District 06 Race \u2013 Nov 02, 2010|publisher=Our Campaigns|accessdate=November 19, 2016}}</ref> He was again unopposed in the 2012 and 2014 primaries,<ref name=\"Kazanow\">{{cite web|url=http://go.galegroup.com/ps/retrieve.do?tabID=T004&resultListType=RESULT_LIST&searchResultsType=SingleTab&searchType=AdvancedSearchForm&currentPosition=19&docId=GALE%7CA297946045&docType=Article&sort=DA-ASC-SORT&contentSegment=&prodId=STND&contentSet=GALE%7CA297946045&searchId=R2&userGroupName=fairfax_main&inPS=true|author=Daniel Malloy|title=U.S. Congress: Incumbents Likely to Survive Voters' Discontent: Georgia Contests More Like Walks than Races|work=The Atlanta Journal-Constitution|date=July 29, 2012|accessdate=October 11, 2017}} {{subscription required|via=Infotrac Newsstand}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ourcampaigns.com/RaceDetail.html?RaceID=783422|title=GA District 06 - R Primary Race - May 20, 2014|publisher=Our Campaigns|accessdate=October 11, 2017}} {{subscription required|via=Infotrac Newsstand}}</ref> but faced Democratic challengers each year in November.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://go.galegroup.com/ps/retrieve.do?tabID=T004&resultListType=RESULT_LIST&searchResultsType=SingleTab&searchType=AdvancedSearchForm&currentPosition=7&docId=GALE%7CA307304776&docType=Article&sort=DA-ASC-SORT&contentSegment=&prodId=STND&contentSet=GALE%7CA307304776&searchId=R1&userGroupName=fairfax_main&inPS=true|author1=Daniel Malloy|author2=Jeremy Redmon|author3=Aaroun Gould Sheinin|title=Congressional Races in Metro Atlanta Districts|work=The Atlanta Journal-Constitution|date=November 4, 2012|accessdate=October 11, 2017}} {{subscription required|via=Infotrac Newsstand}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://go.galegroup.com/ps/retrieve.do?tabID=T004&resultListType=RESULT_LIST&searchResultsType=SingleTab&searchType=BasicSearchForm&currentPosition=5&docId=GALE%7CA385792349&docType=Article&sort=DA-ASC-SORT&contentSegment=&prodId=STND&contentSet=GALE%7CA385792349&searchId=R18&userGroupName=fairfax_main&inPS=true|author=Jeremy Redmon|title=House 10th District Race: Candidates Have Activist Roots: Civil Rights Attorney, Former Baptist Minister Vying for Seat in Congress|work=The Atlanta Journal-Constitution|date=October 14, 2014|accessdate=October 11, 2017}} {{subscription required|via=Infotrac Newsstand}}</ref> In 2012, Jeff Kazanow, a business consultant, narrowly beat Robert Montigel, a small-business owner, in the 6th district's Democratic primary.<ref name=\"Kazanow\"/><ref>{{cite web|url=http://go.galegroup.com/ps/retrieve.do?tabID=T004&resultListType=RESULT_LIST&searchResultsType=SingleTab&searchType=BasicSearchForm&currentPosition=4&docId=GALE%7CA298366028&docType=Article&sort=DA-ASC-SORT&contentSegment=&prodId=STND&contentSet=GALE%7CA298366028&searchId=R25&userGroupName=fairfax_main&inPS=true|author=''The Atlanta Journal-Constitution'' staff|title=AJC Election Central: Results|work=The Atlanta Journal-Constitution|date=August 2, 2012|accessdate=October 11, 2017}} {{subscription required|via=Infotrac Newsstand}}</ref> Montigel went onto become the district's Democratic nominee in 2014.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://go.galegroup.com/ps/retrieve.do?tabID=T004&resultListType=RESULT_LIST&searchResultsType=SingleTab&searchType=BasicSearchForm&currentPosition=6&docId=GALE%7CA388389234&docType=Article&sort=DA-ASC-SORT&contentSegment=&prodId=STND&contentSet=GALE%7CA388389234&searchId=R18&userGroupName=fairfax_main&inPS=true|author=Jaime Sarrio|title=Voters Guide: What's on the Ballot: Headed to the Polls this Tuesday? Here's Everything You Need to Know About Metro Atlanta's Hottest Races|work=The Atlanta Journal-Constitution|date=November 2, 2014|accessdate=October 11, 2017}} {{subscription required|via=Infotrac Newsstand}}</ref> Price won re-election to a fifth term in 2012, beating Kazanow with 64% of the vote,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://go.galegroup.com/ps/retrieve.do?tabID=T004&resultListType=RESULT_LIST&searchResultsType=SingleTab&searchType=AdvancedSearchForm&currentPosition=9&docId=GALE%7CA307696575&docType=Statistical+table&sort=DA-ASC-SORT&contentSegment=&prodId=STND&contentSet=GALE%7CA307696575&searchId=R1&userGroupName=fairfax_main&inPS=true|author=''USA Today'' staff|title=Election 2012: House|work=[[USA Today]]|date=November 7, 2012|accessdate=October 11, 2017}} {{subscription required|via=Infotrac Newsstand}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ourcampaigns.com/RaceDetail.html?RaceID=753473|title=GA District 06 Race \u2013 Nov 06, 2012|publisher=Our Campaigns|accessdate=November 19, 2016}}</ref>\nand to a sixth term in 2014, beating Montigel with 66% of the vote.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://go.galegroup.com/ps/retrieve.do?tabID=T004&resultListType=RESULT_LIST&searchResultsType=SingleTab&searchType=BasicSearchForm&currentPosition=9&docId=GALE%7CA388831381&docType=List&sort=DA-ASC-SORT&contentSegment=&prodId=STND&contentSet=GALE%7CA388831381&searchId=R18&userGroupName=fairfax_main&inPS=true|author=''USA Today'' staff|title=House|work=USA Today|date=November 5, 2014|accessdate=October 11, 2017}} {{subscription required|via=Infotrac Newsstand}}</ref>\n\n;2016\nAfter being unopposed in the 2016 Republican primary, Price faced Democratic challenger [[Rodney Stooksbury]] in the general election.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://go.galegroup.com/ps/retrieve.do?tabID=T004&resultListType=RESULT_LIST&searchResultsType=SingleTab&searchType=BasicSearchForm&currentPosition=1&docId=GALE%7CA453225462&docType=Article&sort=DA-ASC-SORT&contentSegment=&prodId=STND&contentSet=GALE%7CA453225462&searchId=R1&userGroupName=fairfax_main&inPS=true|author=''The Associated Press'' staff|title=GA-Uncontested|work=[[The Associated Press]]|date=May 24, 2016|accessdate=October 11, 2017}} {{subscription required|via=Infotrac Newsstand}}</ref> Stooksbury, said to be a retired [[aeronautic]],<ref>{{cite web|url=http://go.galegroup.com/ps/retrieve.do?tabID=T004&resultListType=RESULT_LIST&searchResultsType=SingleTab&searchType=BasicSearchForm&currentPosition=2&docId=GALE%7CA467173570&docType=Article&sort=DA-ASC-SORT&contentSegment=&prodId=STND&contentSet=GALE%7CA467173570&searchId=R1&userGroupName=fairfax_main&inPS=true|author=Tamar Hallerman|title=Congressional Races: Little-known Challengers Press On: Providing Competition Drives Candidates Who Face an Uphill Battle|work=The Atlanta Journal-Constitution|date=October 20, 2016|accessdate=October 11, 2017}} {{subscription required|via=Infotrac Newsstand}}</ref> was described by the media as a \"ghost candidate\", as he had no public photographs, official website, or social media presence. When [[CBS46]] sent a reporter to his listed address, there was no answer, and Stooksbury's supposed neighbors had never heard of him.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.cbs46.com/story/33632482/who-is-the-ghost-candidate-for-us-6th-district|author=Astrid Martinez|title=Who is the 'ghost' candidate for U.S. 6th district?|work=[[CBS46]]|date=November 4, 2016|accessdate=October 11, 2017}}</ref> The Stooksbury campaign spent a mere $346.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.cnbc.com/2017/04/17/georgia-house-special-election-trump-slams-democrat-jon-ossoff.html|author1=Jacob Pramuk|author2=John W. Schoen|title=Trump Chimes in on Georgia Congressional Election as Cash Flow to Help - or Stop - a 30-Year-Old Democrat|work=[[CNBC]]|date=April 17, 2017|accessdate=October 11, 2017}}</ref> Despite the handicap of possibly not existing, Stooksbury performed better than any of his predecessors - Price won the election, but only carried 61% of the vote.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://go.galegroup.com/ps/retrieve.do?tabID=T004&resultListType=RESULT_LIST&searchResultsType=SingleTab&searchType=BasicSearchForm&currentPosition=3&docId=GALE%7CA470000437&docType=Brief+article&sort=DA-ASC-SORT&contentSegment=&prodId=STND&contentSet=GALE%7CA470000437&searchId=R1&userGroupName=fairfax_main&inPS=true|author=''US Official News'' staff|title=US General Election 2016 Results of State Georgia: U.S. Representative, District 6|work=US Official News|date=November 12, 2016|accessdate=October 11, 2017}} {{subscription required|via=Infotrac Newsstand}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.nytimes.com/elections/results/georgia-house-district-6-price-stooksbury|title=Georgia U.S. House 6th District Results: Tom Price Wins|access-date=2017-03-06}}</ref>\n\n===Tenure===\nPrice was chosen to serve as chairman of the [[Republican Study Committee]] in November 2008, upon being elected to his third term in Congress.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://go.galegroup.com/ps/retrieve.do?tabID=T004&resultListType=RESULT_LIST&searchResultsType=SingleTab&searchType=AdvancedSearchForm&currentPosition=20&docId=GALE%7CA189557202&docType=Brief+article&sort=DA-ASC-SORT&contentSegment=&prodId=STND&contentSet=GALE%7CA189557202&searchId=R1&userGroupName=fairfax_main&inPS=true|author=Julia Malone|title=Georgian New Chair of GOP Group|work=The Atlanta Journal-Constitution|date=November 21, 2008|accessdate=November 2, 2017}} {{subscription required|via=Infotrac Newsstand}}</ref> Two years later, he was chosen to serve as chairman of the [[House Republican Policy Committee]], which made him the \"fifth highest ranking Republican in the House\".<ref>{{cite web|url=http://go.galegroup.com/ps/retrieve.do?tabID=T004&resultListType=RESULT_LIST&searchResultsType=SingleTab&searchType=AdvancedSearchForm&currentPosition=16&docId=GALE%7CA242392502&docType=Article&sort=DA-ASC-SORT&contentSegment=&prodId=STND&contentSet=GALE%7CA242392502&searchId=R2&userGroupName=fairfax_main&inPS=true|author=Bob Keefe|title=Boehner, Pelosi picked by parties: Reps. Price of Roswell, Westmoreland of Coweta named to posts|work=The Atlanta Journal-Constitution|date=November 18, 2010|accessdate=November 2, 2017}} {{subscription required|via=Infotrac Newsstand}}</ref> Price was also chosen in 2010 to serve on the [[United States House Committee on Ways and Means|Ways and Means Committee]]<ref>{{cite web|url=http://go.galegroup.com/ps/retrieve.do?tabID=T004&resultListType=RESULT_LIST&searchResultsType=SingleTab&searchType=AdvancedSearchForm&currentPosition=76&docId=GALE%7CA244428699&docType=Brief+article&sort=DA-ASC-SORT&contentSegment=&prodId=STND&contentSet=GALE%7CA244428699&searchId=R3&userGroupName=fairfax_main&inPS=true|author=Bob Keefe|title=State Lawmakers Get Key Positions: 'Fairly Young Team' to Get Seats on Several Powerful Committees|work=The Atlanta Journal-Constitution|date=December 15, 2010|accessdate=November 2, 2017}} {{subscription required|via=Infotrac Newsstand}}</ref> and on the [[United States House Committee on the Budget|Budget Committee]].<ref>{{cite press release|url=http://go.galegroup.com/ps/retrieve.do?tabID=T004&resultListType=RESULT_LIST&searchResultsType=SingleTab&searchType=AdvancedSearchForm&currentPosition=21&docId=GALE%7CA312409667&docType=Brief+article&sort=DA-ASC-SORT&contentSegment=&prodId=STND&contentSet=GALE%7CA312409667&searchId=R4&userGroupName=fairfax_main&inPS=true|title=Price Named Vice Chair of Budget Committee|publisher=The office of Representative Tom Price|date=December 18, 2012|accessdate=November 2, 2017}} {{subscription required|via=Infotrac Newsstand}}</ref> In December 2012, he was named Vice-Chair of the Budget Committee, serving under [[Paul Ryan]],<ref>{{cite web|url=http://go.galegroup.com/ps/retrieve.do?tabID=T004&resultListType=RESULT_LIST&searchResultsType=SingleTab&searchType=AdvancedSearchForm&currentPosition=22&docId=GALE%7CA312479581&docType=Article&sort=DA-ASC-SORT&contentSegment=&prodId=STND&contentSet=GALE%7CA312479581&searchId=R4&userGroupName=fairfax_main&inPS=true|author1=Patrick Fox|author2=Mark Woolsey|author3=Nancy Badertscher|title=Northside: Northside: County extends local business initiative: North Fulton, Cherokee, Forsyth|work=The Atlanta Journal-Constitution|date=December 19, 2012|accessdate=November 2, 2017}} {{subscription required|via=Infotrac Newsstand}}</ref> and in November 2014, Price succeeded Ryan as the committee's chairman.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://go.galegroup.com/ps/retrieve.do?tabID=T004&resultListType=RESULT_LIST&searchResultsType=SingleTab&searchType=AdvancedSearchForm&currentPosition=105&docId=GALE%7CA390928715&docType=Article&sort=DA-ASC-SORT&contentSegment=&prodId=STND&contentSet=GALE%7CA390928715&searchId=R1&userGroupName=fairfax_main&inPS=true|author=Lori Montgomery|title=Why the Right Loves the Democratic Appointee Who Runs the Congressional Committee Budget Office|work=The Washington Post|date=November 20, 2014|accessdate=November 2, 2017}} {{subscription required|via=Infotrac Newsstand}}</ref>\n\nIn 2012, Price sought the position of [[Republican Conference Chairman]], which would have made him the fourth highest ranking Republican in the House. He was endorsed by Ryan,<ref name=\"Ryan Endorsed\">{{cite web|url=http://go.galegroup.com/ps/retrieve.do?tabID=T004&resultListType=RESULT_LIST&searchResultsType=SingleTab&searchType=AdvancedSearchForm&currentPosition=30&docId=GALE%7CA308319315&docType=Brief+article&sort=DA-ASC-SORT&contentSegment=&prodId=STND&contentSet=GALE%7CA308319315&searchId=R3&userGroupName=fairfax_main&inPS=true|author=CNN Political Unit|title=Paul Ryan Backs Price for Top GOP Leadership Role|work=[[CNN]]|date=November 13, 2012|accessdate=November 2, 2017}} {{subscription required|via=Infotrac Newsstand}}</ref> as well as by the [[Tea Party movement|Tea Party]]-affiliated organization [[FreedomWorks]], conservative political commentator [[Erick Erickson]],<ref name=\"AJC Conference\">{{cite web|url=http://go.galegroup.com/ps/retrieve.do?tabID=T004&resultListType=RESULT_LIST&searchResultsType=SingleTab&searchType=AdvancedSearchForm&currentPosition=32&docId=GALE%7CA308392452&docType=Conference+news&sort=DA-ASC-SORT&contentSegment=&prodId=STND&contentSet=GALE%7CA308392452&searchId=R3&userGroupName=fairfax_main&inPS=true|author=Daniel Malloy|title=Congress: Vote Today Could Push Price Up GOP Ladder: Conservative GOP Lawmaker Vying for Conference Chairman|work=The Atlanta Journal-Constitution|date=November 14, 2012|accessdate=November 2, 2017}} {{subscription required|via=Infotrac Newsstand}}</ref> future Vice-President and then-governor of Indiana [[Mike Pence]], and outgoing Republican Conference Chairman [[Jeb Hensarling]].<ref name=\"NY Conference\">{{cite web|url=http://go.galegroup.com/ps/retrieve.do?tabID=T004&resultListType=RESULT_LIST&searchResultsType=SingleTab&searchType=AdvancedSearchForm&currentPosition=34&docId=GALE%7CA308345078&docType=Article&sort=DA-ASC-SORT&contentSegment=&prodId=STND&contentSet=GALE%7CA308345078&searchId=R3&userGroupName=fairfax_main&inPS=true|author=Jonathan Weisman|title=Congress Resumes with a G.O.P. Leadership Fight|work=The New York Times|date=November 14, 2012|accessdate=November 2, 2017}} {{subscription required|via=Infotrac Newsstand}}</ref> Ryan said of Price, \"He was instrumental in drafting our House Republican budget. His vocal leadership on issues like health care, tax reform, and fiscal matters has been vital to our messaging and policy efforts. No one will work harder than Congressman Price at building a strong and compelling communications and policy strategy that reflects the will of our membership and the needs of the nation.\"<ref name=\"Ryan Endorsed\"/> Although then-[[Speaker of the United States House of Representatives|Speaker of the House]] [[John Boehner]] did not publicly endorse anyone in the race, he was seen as preferring Price's challenger for the position, [[Cathy McMorris Rodgers]], and offered Price a separate position if he dropped out of the race for Conference Chairman - Price turned down the offer.<ref name=\"NY Conference\"/><ref name=\"AJC Conference\"/><ref name=\"Daily Herald Conference\">{{cite web|url=http://go.galegroup.com/ps/retrieve.do?tabID=T004&resultListType=RESULT_LIST&searchResultsType=SingleTab&searchType=AdvancedSearchForm&currentPosition=38&docId=GALE%7CA309324711&docType=Article&sort=DA-ASC-SORT&contentSegment=&prodId=STND&contentSet=GALE%7CA309324711&searchId=R3&userGroupName=fairfax_main&inPS=true|author=Associated Press|title=House GOP Picks Woman for a Top Leadership Post|work=[[Daily Herald (Arlington Heights)|Daily Herald]]|date=November 15, 2012|accessdate=November 2, 2017}} {{subscription required|via=Infotrac Newsstand}}</ref> He lost the election to McMorris Rodgers in November.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://go.galegroup.com/ps/retrieve.do?tabID=T004&resultListType=RESULT_LIST&searchResultsType=SingleTab&searchType=AdvancedSearchForm&currentPosition=33&docId=GALE%7CA308467105&docType=Brief+article&sort=DA-ASC-SORT&contentSegment=&prodId=STND&contentSet=GALE%7CA308467105&searchId=R3&userGroupName=fairfax_main&inPS=true|author=CNN Political Unit|title=Boehner Renominated for House Speaker|work=CNN|date=November 14, 2012|accessdate=November 2, 2017}} {{subscription required|via=Infotrac Newsstand}}</ref><ref name=\"Rise in House\">{{cite web|url=http://go.galegroup.com/ps/retrieve.do?tabID=T004&resultListType=RESULT_LIST&searchResultsType=SingleTab&searchType=AdvancedSearchForm&currentPosition=35&docId=GALE%7CA308539853&docType=Article&sort=DA-ASC-SORT&contentSegment=&prodId=STND&contentSet=GALE%7CA308539853&searchId=R3&userGroupName=fairfax_main&inPS=true|author=Daniel Malloy|title=Price's Rise in House Blocked: Conservative Roswell Rep an Occasional Thorn in GOP Leaders' Side|work=The Atlanta Journal-Constitution|date=November 15, 2012|accessdate=November 2, 2017}} {{subscription required|via=Infotrac Newsstand}}</ref>\n\nThat same year, Price was considered as a possible primary challenger for Republican senator [[Saxby Chambliss]],<ref name=\"AJC Conference\"/><ref>{{cite web|url=http://go.galegroup.com/ps/retrieve.do?tabID=T004&resultListType=RESULT_LIST&searchResultsType=SingleTab&searchType=AdvancedSearchForm&currentPosition=2&docId=GALE%7CA315640383&docType=Broadcast+transcript&sort=Relevance&contentSegment=&prodId=STND&contentSet=GALE%7CA315640383&searchId=R10&userGroupName=fairfax_main&inPS=true|author=''CQ News'' staff|title=CQ News|work=[[CQ Press]]|date=2012|accessdate=November 4, 2017}} {{subscription required|via=Infotrac Newsstand}}</ref> and in 2014, Price was considered as a possible replacement for [[Eric Cantor]] as the House [[Majority Leader of the United States House of Representatives|Majority Leader]], but Price ultimately decided against pursuing either of these positions.<ref name=\"myAJC\"/><ref>{{cite web|url=http://go.galegroup.com/ps/retrieve.do?tabID=T004&resultListType=RESULT_LIST&searchResultsType=SingleTab&searchType=AdvancedSearchForm&currentPosition=8&docId=GALE%7CA370985471&docType=Article&sort=DA-ASC-SORT&contentSegment=&prodId=STND&contentSet=GALE%7CA370985471&searchId=R3&userGroupName=fairfax_main&inPS=true|author=Daniel Malloy|title=Cantor's loss puts eyes on Georgia: State's U.S. reps avoid leadership jockeying --- for now, at least|work=The Atlanta Journal-Constitution|date=June 12, 2014|accessdate=November 4, 2017}} {{subscription required|via=Infotrac Newsstand}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://go.galegroup.com/ps/retrieve.do?tabID=T004&resultListType=RESULT_LIST&searchResultsType=SingleTab&searchType=AdvancedSearchForm&currentPosition=9&docId=GALE%7CA371692548&docType=Brief+article%2C+Broadcast+transcript&sort=DA-ASC-SORT&contentSegment=&prodId=STND&contentSet=GALE%7CA371692548&searchId=R3&userGroupName=fairfax_main&inPS=true|author=Steven T. Dennis|title=CQ News|work=CQ Press|date=2014|accessdate=November 4, 2017}} {{subscription required|via=Infotrac Newsstand}}</ref>\n\nIn 2013, the [[American Conservative Union]] named Price one of the most conservative members of Congress, giving him a 100% approval rating.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://go.galegroup.com/ps/retrieve.do?tabID=T004&resultListType=RESULT_LIST&searchResultsType=SingleTab&searchType=AdvancedSearchForm&currentPosition=2&docId=GALE%7CA319742181&docType=Brief+article&sort=Relevance&contentSegment=&prodId=STND&contentSet=GALE%7CA319742181&searchId=R1&userGroupName=fairfax_main&inPS=true|author=CNN Political Unit|title=The Most Conservative Members of Congress Are....|work=CNN|date=February 21, 2013|accessdate=November 4, 2017}} {{subscription required|via=Infotrac Newsstand}}</ref> Price was also described as one of the most conservative members of Congress by the ''Atlanta Journal-Constitution'' and the ''[[New York Times]]''.<ref name=\"Rise in House\"/><ref name=\"NY Conference\"/>\n\nPrice is a member of the [[Republican Main Street Partnership]].<ref>{{cite web|title=Members|author=|url=https://republicanmainstreet.org/members/|format=|publisher=Republican Mains Street Partnership|date=|accessdate=October 4, 2017}}</ref>\n\n===Voting record and political views===\n\n====Healthcare====\n[[File:U.S. Congressman Tom Price speaking at the 2010 Conservative Political Action Conference (CPAC).jpg|thumb|Congressman Price speaking at the 2010 [[Conservative Political Action Conference]] (CPAC)]]In response to questions as to whether or not [[vaccine]]s cause [[autism]], Price stated in January 2017 \"I think the science in that instance is that it does not\".<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.huffingtonpost.com/entry/tom-price-vaccine_us_58877d7be4b0e3a7356be531 |title=Tom Price Tries To Assure Senators He's Not Crazy On Vaccines |publisher=[[The Huffington Post]] |author=Arthur Delaney |date=January 24, 2017}}</ref> Price said in March 2017 that it should be up to individual states to determine whether [[vaccine controversies|vaccinations should be required]] - a position that is in keeping with current U.S. law, which does not require vaccinations on a federal level. All fifty states do however, have laws requiring that children in public schools be vaccinated.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.politico.com/story/2017/03/price-obamacare-medicaid-rollback-236114|title=Price dodges on Medicaid rollback, immunization|work=POLITICO|access-date=2017-03-16}}</ref>\n\nAs a U.S. Congressman, Price voted multiple times to repeal the [[Patient Protection and Affordable Care Act]],<ref name=\"obamacarefoe\">{{cite news |url=https://www.npr.org/sections/health-shots/2016/11/28/502566553/trump-chooses-rep-tom-price-an-obamacare-foe-to-run-hhs |title=Trump Chooses Rep. Tom Price, An Obamacare Foe, To Run HHS |publisher=[[NPR]] |author=Joe Neel |date=November 28, 2016}}</ref> as well as portions of the [[Health Care and Education Reconciliation Act of 2010]].<ref>{{cite web|title=Final Vote Results for Roll Call 9: H RES 26|url=http://clerk.house.gov/evs/2011/roll009.xml|website=clerk.house.gov|publisher=clerk.house.gov|accessdate=January 7, 2011}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Final Vote Results for Roll Call 10: H RES 26|url=http://clerk.house.gov/evs/2011/roll010.xml|website=clerk.house.gov|publisher=clerk.house.gov|accessdate=January 7, 2011}}</ref> Price introduced his first post-Obamacare bill as early as 2009, thereafter reintroducing updated versions in every Congress since that point.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.forbes.com/sites/theapothecary/2015/05/26/prices-empowering-patients-first-act-gets-better-with-age/#30047eb659c8|title=Price's Empowering Patients First Act Gets Better with Age|author=John Graham|work=The Apothecary|publisher=''[[Forbes]]''|accessdate=2017-03-07}}</ref> In May 2015, as [[United States House Committee on the Budget|House Budget Committee]] chairman, Price released health care legislation which was described by [[William Kristol|Bill Kristol]] of the ''[[National Review]]'' as \"the strongest Obamacare alternative offered in Congress to date.\"<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.nationalreview.com/article/418565/tom-prices-new-conservative-obamacare-alternative-just-what-dr-ordered-jeffrey-h|title=Tom Price's New Conservative Obamacare Alternative Is Just What the Dr. Ordered|work=National Review|access-date=2017-03-07|language=en}}</ref> Greg Sargent of the ''[[Washington Post]]'' wrote of the bill, \"it's good to have a fleshed out plan, because it helps clarify the differences between the parties on health reform.\"<ref name=\"Republicans Brace\">{{cite web|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/blogs/plum-line/wp/2015/05/15/republicans-brace-for-for-glorious-victory-over-obamacare/|author=Greg Sargent|title=Republicans brace for glorious victory over Obamacare|work=The Washington Post|date=May 15, 2015|accessdate=October 11, 2017}}</ref> Sargent also wrote that \"GOP reforms would likely translate into lower-quality plans and a coverage expansion that would benefit fewer people. But that would be the trade-off Republicans would make to achieve their goal of less government spending and interference in the market than that which occurs under Obamacare.\"<ref name=\"Republicans Brace\"/> In 2017, after Price was nominated to be [[Secretary of Health and Human Services]], [[NPR]] wrote that Price's 2015 bill would be seen as \"one of the main paths forward to repeal portions of the ACA.\"<ref name=\"obamacarefoe\"/>\n\nPrice has supported [[Paul Ryan]]'s plan to [[Privatization|privatize]] [[Medicare (United States)|Medicare]].<ref name=\"Fast Facts\"/>\n\nPrice voted against the [[Family Smoking Prevention and Tobacco Control Act]], a law that for the first time gave the [[Food and Drug Administration]] regulatory jurisdiction over tobacco products, i.e. the power to regulate tobacco as a drug.<ref name=obamacarefoe/>\n\n====Abortion====\nPrice opposes [[abortion]] and voted to withdraw federal funding for [[Planned Parenthood]].<ref name=\"obamacarefoe\"/> In 2005, he [[Sponsor (legislative)|co-sponsored]] the Right to Life Act, which would have defined life as beginning at the moment of [[Fertilization|conception]], therefore banning most abortions and many forms of [[contraception]].<ref name=\"Health Czar\">{{cite web|url=https://www.thedailybeast.com/trump-health-czar-tom-price-is-a-nightmare-for-women|author=Erin Gloria Ryan|title=Trump Health Czar Tom Price Is a Nightmare for Women|work=[[The Daily Beast]]|date=November 29, 2016|accessdate=October 15, 2017}}</ref> On multiple occasions, Price supported the proposed Pain-Capable Unborn Child Protection Act, which if passed, would have implemented a nationwide [[Late termination of pregnancy#United States 2|ban on abortions occurring after the twentieth week of pregnancy]].<ref name=\"Health Czar\"/><ref name=\":2\" /><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.usatoday.com/story/news/politics/elections/2016/2016/11/28/reports-rep-tom-price-trumps-pick-health-and-human-services-dept/94578690/|author1=David Jackson|author2=Steph Solis|title=Rep. Tom Price is Trump's pick for Health and Human Services Dept.|work=USA Today|date=November 28, 2016|accessdate=October 15, 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite press release|url=https://www.highbeam.com/doc/1G1-334301432.html|title=Price Votes to Protect the Sanctity of Life|publisher=Office of Georgia Representative Tom Price|date=June 18, 2013|accessdate=October 15, 2017}} {{subscription required|via=Infotrac Newsstand}}</ref>\n\nPrice supported the proposed Protect Life Act of 2011,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://votesmart.org/public-statement/643441/price-statement-on-the-protect-life-act/?search=abortion|title=Price Statement on the Protect Life Act|work=[[Vote Smart]]|accessdate=November 19, 2016}}</ref> which would have amended the Patient Protection and Affordable Care Act (often abbreviated as the ACA) to deny federal subsidies to any health insurance plans offering abortion coverage - exceptions would have been allowed in the cases of rape, incest, or when a mother's life is at risk.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://go.galegroup.com/ps/i.do?p=STND&sw=w&u=fairfax_main&v=2.1&id=GALE%7CA269553282&it=r&asid=5b42f0f20e07c13a18567a73fc4964b1|author=Paige Winfield Cunningham|title=House GOP Revives Abortion Issue, Irks Obama|work=[[The Washington Times]]|date=October 13, 2011|accessdate=October 14, 2017}} {{subscription required|via=Infotrac Newsstand}}</ref><ref>{{cite press release|url=http://go.galegroup.com/ps/i.do?p=STND&sw=w&u=fairfax_main&v=2.1&id=GALE%7CA269608518&it=r&asid=0132e87c20b0da828cedf4748e36cfc0|title=National Right to Life Applauds U.S. House Approval of Protect Life Act, Slams President Obama for Threat to Protect Abortion Subsidies with Veto|publisher=[[National Right to Life Committee]]|date=October 13, 2011|accessdate=October 14, 2017}} {{subscription required|via=Infotrac Newsstand}}</ref> The ACA already banned federal subsidies from being used to cover abortions, but did allow health insurance plans covering abortions to receive federal subsidies, so long as such funding was not directly used for abortion coverage.<ref>{{cite press release|url=http://go.galegroup.com/ps/i.do?p=STND&sw=w&u=fairfax_main&v=2.1&id=GALE%7CA269696246&it=r&asid=69151297bd3f6fee88d71fa576102fe5|title=The Protect Life Act Would Actually Threaten Women's Lives|publisher=[[Center for American Progress]]|date=October 14, 2011|accessdate=October 14, 2017}} {{subscription required|via=Infotrac Newsstand}}</ref> The Protect Life Act would have also allowed hospitals to refuse life-saving abortions to women in emergency situations.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://go.galegroup.com/ps/i.do?p=STND&sw=w&u=fairfax_main&v=2.1&id=GALE%7CA248695387&it=r&asid=4699b1d2a70be66a9d2553002d965752|author=Felicia Sonmez|title='Protect Life' Bill to Ban Federal Abortion Funding is Debated|date=February 9, 2011|accessdate=October 14, 2017}} {{subscription required|via=Infotrac Newsstand}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.huffingtonpost.com/2011/10/13/protect-life-act-passes-house-of-representatives_n_1009876.html|title=House Passes Controversial Anti-Abortion Bill|last=Bassett|first=Laura|date=October 13, 2011|publisher=[[The Huffington Post]]}}</ref>\n\nIn 2013, Price co-sponsored the Health Care Conscience Rights Act,<ref name=\":2\" /> which would have amended the ACA to allow all employers opposed to abortion and contraception to offer health insurance plans that do not cover these services. The bill also would have amended the [[Public Health Service Act]] to strengthen protections of health care workers who refuse to participate in abortion procedures.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.govtrack.us/congress/bills/114/hr940/summary#libraryofcongress|author=Congressional Research Service|title=H.R. 940 (114th): Health Care Conscience Rights Act|work=[[GovTrack]]|date=February 12, 2015|accessdate=October 15, 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite press release|url=http://go.galegroup.com/ps/retrieve.do?tabID=T004&resultListType=RESULT_LIST&searchResultsType=SingleTab&searchType=AdvancedSearchForm&currentPosition=1&docId=GALE%7CA321207455&docType=Article&sort=Relevance&contentSegment=&prodId=STND&contentSet=GALE%7CA321207455&searchId=R1&userGroupName=fairfax_main&inPS=true|title=Black, Fortenberry & Fleming Introduce Health Care Conscience Rights Act to Stop Obama Administration's Assault on Religious Freedom|publisher=The office of Representative [[Diane Black]]|date=March 5, 2013|accessdate=October 15, 2017}} {{subscription required|via=Infotrac Newsstand}}</ref><ref>{{cite press release|url=https://www.highbeam.com/doc/1G1-323220347.html|title=Luetkemeyer Co-Sponsors Bill Backing Health Care Conscience Protections Including Abortion|publisher=The office of Representative [[Blaine Luetkemeyer]]|date=March 22, 2013|accessdate=October 15, 2017}} {{subscription required|via=HighBeam}}</ref><ref>{{cite press release|url=http://www.nationalrighttolifenews.org/news/2017/02/senate-confirms-dr-price-as-hhs-secretary/#.WeO-MGhSxPY|title=Senate Confirms Dr. Price as HHS Secretary|publisher=National Right to Life Committee|date=February 13, 2017|accessdate=October 15, 2017}}</ref>\n\nAmong the ACA's other provisions, Price is opposed to the bill's elimination, under most health insurance plans, of [[co-pay]]s for [[birth control]]. Price defended his position on this issue in a 2012 interview, by suggesting that there are no women in the country who have ever struggled to pay for birth control. He said, \"Bring me one woman who has been left behind. Bring me one. There's not one.\"<ref name=\"Atlantic co-pay\">{{cite web|url=https://www.theatlantic.com/health/archive/2016/11/tom-price-not-one-woman-cant-afford-birth-control/509003/|author=Olga Khazan|title=Tom Price: 'Not One' Woman Struggled to Afford Birth Control|work=[[The Atlantic]]|date=November 29, 2016|accessdate=October 16, 2017}}</ref><ref name=\"PBS co-pay\">{{cite web|url=http://www.pbs.org/newshour/rundown/birth-control-tom-price-health-secretary/|author=Rebecca Robins|title=Birth Control Emerges as Rallying Cry Against Trump's Pick for Health Secretary|work=[[PBS News Hour]]|date=December 4, 2016|accessdate=October 16, 2017}}</ref><ref name=\"Huffington co-pay\">{{cite web|url=https://www.huffingtonpost.com/entry/tom-price-contraception-access_us_583dd2e8e4b0860d6116b6eb|author=Travis Waldron|title=In 2012, Trump's Pick For HHS Said 'Not One Woman' Lacked Access To Birth Control|work=The Huffington Post|date=November 29, 2016|accessdate=October 16, 2017}}</ref> Numerous media outlets have refuted this assertion.<ref name=\"Atlantic co-pay\"/><ref name=\"PBS co-pay\"/><ref name=\"Huffington co-pay\"/><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/opinions/the-trump-administrations-birth-control-overhaul-could-do-serious-harm/2017/06/07/f18f08e8-4abe-11e7-a186-60c031eab644_story.html|author=''The Washington Post'' editorial board|title=The Trump Administration's Birth Control Overhaul Could Do Serious Harm|work=The Washington Post|date=June 7, 2017|accessdate=October 16, 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://motto.time.com/4791171/birth-control-executive-order-religion/|author=Jessica Gonz\u00e1lez-Rojas|title=Access to Birth Control Is Not a Religious Debate|work=Motto|publisher=[[Time (magazine)|Time]]|date=March 23, 2017|accessdate=October 16, 2017}}</ref> In 2017, during his confirmation hearing to become Secretary of Health and Human Services, Price was questioned about this comment and responded, \"What I meant is that when I had patients in my office who could not afford a medication we did everything we could to make sure they could have it. There are avenues in the health care system that doctors and hospitals take to make sure people can get the health care they need.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.usnews.com/news/health-care-news/articles/2017-01-18/tom-price-leaves-door-open-to-gutting-obamacares-free-birth-control-provision|author=Kimberly Leonard|title=Tom Price Leaves Door Open to Gutting Obamacare's Free Birth Control Provision|work=[[U.S. News and World Report]]|date=January 18, 2017|accessdate=October 16, 2017}}</ref>\n\nPrice has received perfect scores from the [[National Right to Life Committee]], while receiving scores of zero from both Planned Parenthood and [[NARAL Pro-Choice America]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://votesmart.org/candidate/evaluations/11853/tom-price/2|title=Tom Price's Ratings and Endorsements on Issue: Abortion|work=Vote Smart|accessdate=November 19, 2016}}</ref> He participated in the [[March for Life (Washington, D.C.)|March for Life]] annually from 2009 through 2013 and also participated in 2015.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://votesmart.org/public-statement/403715/rep-price-statement-on-march-for-life/?search=March%20for%20Life#.WeKpmmhSxPY|title=Price Statement on March for Life|work=Vote Smart|date=January 22, 2009|accessdate=October 14, 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://votesmart.org/public-statement/481055/price-statement-on-the-march-for-life/?search=March%20for%20Life#.WeKowGhSxPY|title=Price Statement on March for Life|work=Vote Smart|date=January 22, 2010|accessdate=October 14, 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://votesmart.org/public-statement/582186/price-statement-on-march-for-life/?search=abortion|title=Price Statement on March for Life|work=Vote Smart|date=January 24, 2011|accessdate=November 19, 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://votesmart.org/public-statement/662889/price-statement-on-march-for-life/?search=March%20for%20Life#.WeKowmhSxPY|title=Price Statement on March for Life|work=Vote Smart|date=January 23, 2012|accessdate=October 14, 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://votesmart.org/public-statement/761749/price-statement-on-40th-anniversary-of-roe-v-wade/?search=March%20for%20Life#.WeKoxGhSxPY|title=Price Statement on March for Life|work=Vote Smart|date=January 22, 2013|accessdate=October 14, 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://votesmart.org/public-statement/946861/price-statement-on-march-for-life/?search=March%20for%20Life#.WeKplGhSxPY|title=Price Statement on March for Life|work=Vote Smart|date=January 22, 2015|accessdate=October 14, 2017}}</ref>\n\n====Economic policy====\n[[File:Price at Roswell town hall meeting.jpg|thumb|Price speaking in [[Roswell, Georgia]], in 2005]]\nIn 2011, Price voted to reduce non-security discretionary spending to 2008 levels<ref>[http://clerk.house.gov/evs/2011/roll017.xml \"Final Vote Results for Roll Call 17: H RES 26\"], http://clerk.house.gov, January 24, 2011.</ref><ref name=\"govtrack.us 43\">{{cite web |url=http://www.govtrack.us/congress/vote.xpd?vote=h2011-18 |title=GovTrack: House Vote On Passage: H. Res. 43: Providing for consideration of the resolution (H. Res. 38) |publisher=Govtrack.us |date=January 24, 2011 |accessdate=November 20, 2011}}</ref><ref name=\"govtrack.us 38\">{{cite web |url=http://www.govtrack.us/congress/vote.xpd?vote=h2011-20 |title=GovTrack: House Vote On Passage: H. Res. 38: Reducing non-security spending to fiscal year 2008 levels or |publisher=Govtrack.us |date=January 25, 2011 |accessdate=November 20, 2011}}</ref> (and subsequently voted against several amendments offered via motions to recommit with instructions).<ref name=\"govtrack.us 19\">{{cite web |url=http://www.govtrack.us/congress/vote.xpd?vote=h2011-19 |title=GovTrack: House Vote No. 19 (Jan 25, 2011) |publisher=Govtrack.us |date=January 25, 2011 |accessdate=November 20, 2011}}</ref>\n\nIn 2013, he was the main sponsor of the Require a PLAN Act (mandating that the President identify a fiscal year in which the budget will be balanced).<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.govtrack.us/congress/bills/113/hr444|title=Require a PLAN Act (2013 \u2013 H.R. 444)|publisher=}}</ref><ref name=GovTrack.us>{{cite web | url=http://www.govtrack.us/congress/bills/113/hr444 |publisher=GovTrack.us|title=H.R. 444 (113th): Require a PLAN Act|accessdate=April 6, 2013}}</ref> He voted for the [[No Budget, No Pay Act]]<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.govtrack.us/congress/bills/113/hr325|title=No Budget, No Pay Act of 2013 (2013 \u2013 H.R. 325)|publisher=}}</ref><ref name=\"GovTrack.us 30\">{{cite web | url=https://www.govtrack.us/congress/votes/113-2013/s11|publisher=GovTrack.us|title=H.R. 325 (113th): No Budget, No Pay Act of 2013|accessdate=April 6, 2013}}</ref> and a resolution establishing a budget for the United States Government for FY 2014 that passed the House of Representatives.<ref name=\"GovTrack.us 25\">{{cite web | url=http://www.govtrack.us/congress/bills/113/hconres25 |title=H.Con.Res. 25 (113th): Establishing the budget for the United States Government for fiscal year 2014 and setting forth appropriate budgetary levels for fiscal years 2015 through 2023.|publisher=GovTrack.us |accessdate=April 6, 2013}}</ref> In 2011, Price voted to prohibit federal funding of [[NPR|National Public Radio]].<ref name=\"govtrack.us 174\">{{cite web|url=http://www.govtrack.us/congress/vote.xpd?vote=h2011-190 |title= House Vote On Passage: H. Res. 174: Providing for consideration of the bill (H.R. 1076) to |publisher=GovTrack |date=March 17, 2011 |accessdate=November 20, 2011}}</ref> Price voted to terminate the Emergency Mortgage Relief Program.<ref name=\"govtrack.us 836\">{{cite web |url=http://www.govtrack.us/congress/vote.xpd?vote=h2011-174 |title=GovTrack: House Vote On Passage: H.R. 836: Emergency Mortgage Relief Program Termination Act |publisher=Govtrack.us |date=March 11, 2011 |accessdate=November 20, 2011}}</ref> Price voted to reduce federal spending and the deficit by terminating taxpayer financing of presidential election campaigns and party conventions.<ref name=\"govtrack.us 22\">{{cite web |url=http://www.govtrack.us/congress/vote.xpd?vote=h2011-22 | title=GovTrack: House Vote No. 22 (Jan 26, 2011) | publisher=Govtrack.us |date=January 26, 2011 |accessdate=November 20, 2011}}</ref>\n\n====Environment, energy, and agriculture====\nPrice rejects the [[Scientific opinion on climate change|scientific consensus on climate change]].<ref name=\"Guardian Environment\">{{cite web|url=https://www.theguardian.com/environment/2016/dec/15/trump-cabinet-climate-change-deniers|author=Mazin Sidahmed|title=Climate Change Denial in the Trump Cabinet: Where do His Nominees Stand?|work=The Guardian|date=December 15, 2016|accessdate=October 26, 2017}}</ref> In 2008, he signed a pledge sponsored by [[Americans for Prosperity]] promising to vote against any [[global warming]] legislation that would raise taxes.<ref>{{cite press release|url=http://americansforprosperity.org/noclimatetax//wp-content/uploads/2008/08/price.pdf|title=Americans for Prosperity Applauds U.S. Representative Tom Price \u2013 Signs No Climate Tax Pledge|publisher=[[Americans for Prosperity]]|date=August 27, 2008|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20141015203652/http://americansforprosperity.org/noclimatetax//wp-content/uploads/2008/08/price.pdf|archivedate=October 15, 2014}}</ref> In 2010, while speaking out against proposed regulations of [[carbon dioxide]], Price said that the science behind global warming was filled with \"errors and obfuscation\".<ref name=\"Guardian Environment\"/><ref>{{cite web|url=https://votesmart.org/public-statement/490191/republicans-continue-to-fight-national-energy-tax#.WfOpQGhSxPa|title=Republicans Continue to Fight National Energy Tax|work=Vote Smart|date=March 2, 2010|accessdate=October 27, 2017}}</ref>\n\nIn 2006, Price voted against the Deep Ocean Energy Resources Act - a bill which maintained the [[Offshore oil and gas in the United States#Federal restrictions|moratorium on most offshore oil and gas drilling in the United States]]. Although the moratorium went onto be lifted two years later, it was reinstated under [[President Barack Obama]], prompting Price to vote in favor of the Reversing Pres. Obama's Offshore Moratorium Act in 2011.\n\nIn 2007, Price voted against the [[No Oil Producing and Exporting Cartels Act|No Oil and Exporting Cartels (NOPEC) Act]], which would have removed [[sovereign immunity]] protections for [[OPEC]], allowing the organization's members to be sued in the U.S. court system.<ref name=\"Issues Energy\"/> Although the bill passed with bi-partisan support in Congress, it was vetoed by President [[George W. Bush]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.huffingtonpost.com/raymond-j-learsy/nopec-no-oil-producing-an_b_1869803.html|author=Raymond J. Learsy|title=NOPEC: ('No Oil Producing and Exporting Cartels Act'): A Presidential Issue and a Test of Political Integrity|work=The Huffington Post|date=November 9, 2012|accessdate=October 26, 2017}}</ref>\n\nThat same year, Price voted against the Creating Long-Term Energy Alternatives for the Nation (CLEAN) Act, which if passed, would have eliminated [[Energy subsidies#United States|tax breaks and subsidies for oil and gas companies]] - the newly raised funds would have then been used to support the development of [[alternative energy]] sources. Price also voted against providing funding for domestically produced [[biofuels]], and on multiple occasions, he voted against providing tax incentives for [[renewable energy]].<ref name=\"Issues Energy\">{{cite web|url=http://www.ontheissues.org/GA/Tom_Price_Energy_+_Oil.htm|title=Tom Price on Energy & Oil|work=On the Issues|accessdate=October 26, 2017}}</ref>\n\nIn 2009, Price voted against the [[American Clean Energy and Security Act]],<ref name=\"Issues Energy\"/> which if passed, would have implemented a [[cap and trade]] system on [[greenhouse gas emissions]]. Although the bill was never voted on in the Senate, the Obama administration proceeded to regulate greenhouse gas emissions through the [[Clean Power Plan]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.eenews.net/stories/1060039422|author1=Amanda Reilly|author2=Kevin Bogardus|title=Climate: 7 years later, failed Waxman-Markey bill still makes waves|work=[[E&E News]]|date=June 27, 2016|accessdate=October 27, 2017}}</ref> In 2011, Price voted for the [[Energy Tax Prevention Act]], which if passed, would have prevented the [[Environmental Protection Agency]] from implementing such regulations.<ref name=\"Issues Energy\"/>\n\nIn 2011, Price supported the Farm Dust Regulation Prevention Act,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://votesmart.org/public-statement/656161/price-statement-on-house-passage-of-farm-dust-regulation-prevention-act/?search=farmers |title=Price Statement on House Passage of Farm Dust Regulation Prevention Act|work=Vote Smart|date=December 8, 2011|accessdate=November 19, 2016}}</ref> which if passed, would have prevented the [[United States Environmental Protection Agency|Environmental Protection Agency]] from regulating the amount of dust produced through various commercial operations,<ref>{{cite|url=http://thehill.com/blogs/floor-action/house/198217-farm-dust-bill-approved-in-house|author=Pete Kasperowicz|author2=Elise Viebeck|title=Farm Dust Bill Approved in House|work=The Hill|date=December 8, 2011|accessdate=October 26, 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.highbeam.com/doc/1G1-295758383.html|author=Sean Lengell|title=All Bills Lead to Jobs in Latest Spin in Congress|work=The Washington Times|date=July 9, 2012|accessdate=October 26, 2017}} {{subscription required|via=HighBeam}}</ref> and the Superfund Common Sense Act, which would have removed [[manure]] from the [[Superfund|federal government's list of hazardous or pollutant substances]].<ref name=\"Issues Environment\">{{cite web|url=http://www.ontheissues.org/GA/Tom_Price_Environment.htm|title=Tom Price on Environment|work=On the Issues|accessdate=October 26, 2017}}</ref> He also voted for the Agricultural Disaster Assistance Act of 2012,<ref>{{cite web |url=http://votesmart.org/bill/votes/41290|title=HR 6233 \u2013 Agricultural Disaster Assistance Act of 2012 \u2013 Voting Record|work=Vote Smart|accessdate=November 19, 2016}}</ref> which had it become law, would have made financial assistance available to ranchers who had lost livestock due to [[drought]]. The cost of the assistance would have been offset by cuts to programs intended to prevent future droughts.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.govtrack.us/congress/bills/112/hr6233|title=Agricultural Disaster Assistance Act of 2012 (2012 \u2013 H.R. 6233)|publisher=}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.highbeam.com/doc/1N1-14078A1DC672DD18.html|author=''Post-Tribune'' staff|title=How They Voted Last Week|work=[[Post-Tribune]]|date=August 5, 2012|accessdate=October 26, 2017}} {{subscription required|via=HighBeam}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.highbeam.com/doc/1G1-298524563.html|author=David Bennet|title=House Passes $383 Million in Disaster Relief|date=August 3, 2012|accessdate=October 26, 2017}} {{subscription required|via=HighBeam}}</ref>\n\nThe [[American Farm Bureau Federation]] gave Price a score of 82% in 2005-2006, 23% in 2007-2008, 66% in 2009-2010, 70% in 2011, and 25% in 2014. Price consistently received 0% approval ratings from the [[National Farmers Union (United States)|National Farmers Union]], during his time in Congress, except for when he received a score of 11% in 2012.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://votesmart.org/candidate/evaluations/11853/tom-price/4|title=Tom Price's Ratings and Endorsements on Issue: Agriculture and Food|work=Vote Smart | accessdate=November 19, 2016}}</ref>\n\nThe [[League of Conservation Voters]] gave Price a lifetime score of 4%.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://scorecard.lcv.org/moc/tom-price|title=National Environmental Scorecard - Representative Tom Price (R)|work=[[League of Conservation Voters]]|accessdate=October 27, 2017}}</ref>\n\n====Foreign policy====\nPrice voted to extend the [[Patriot Act]].<ref name=\"govtrack.us 514\">{{cite web |url=http://www.govtrack.us/congress/vote.xpd?vote=h2011-26 |title=GovTrack: House Vote On Passage: H.R. 514: FISA Sunsets Extension Act of 2011 |publisher=Govtrack.us |date=February 8, 2011 |accessdate=November 20, 2011}}</ref><ref name=\"govtrack.us 79\">{{cite web |url=http://www.govtrack.us/congress/vote.xpd?vote=h2011-29 |title=GovTrack: House Vote On Passage: H. Res. 79: Providing for consideration of the bill (H.R. 514) to extend |publisher=Govtrack.us |date=February 10, 2011 |accessdate=November 20, 2011}}</ref> Price voted against a resolution which would have forced the president to withdraw American forces from Iraq.<ref name=\"govtrack.us 28\">{{cite web | url=http://www.govtrack.us/congress/vote.xpd?vote=h2011-193 |title=GovTrack: House Vote On Passage: H. Con. Res. 28: Directing the President, pursuant to section 5(c) of |publisher=Govtrack.us |date=March 17, 2011 |accessdate=November 20, 2011}}</ref> In 2015, Price stated his belief that states should not have to participate in [[Asylum in the United States|refugee resettlement programs]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://votesmart.org/public-statement/1055042/price-backs-plan-to-strengthen-state-control-over-refugees#.WfdebGhSxPY|title=Price Backs Plan to Strengthen State Control Over Refugees|work=Vote Smart|date=November 19, 2015|accessdate=October 30, 2017}}</ref>\n\nDuring Price's first year in Congress, he voted for the [[United Nations Reform Act of 2005]], which if passed, would have withdrawn up to one-half of US funding for the [[United Nations]], unless various reforms were met. In 2011, Price voted for the United Nations Transparency, Accountability, and Reform Act, which would have limited the kind of funding allowed to be contributed to the United Nations.<ref name=\"Issues FoPo\"/>\n\nIn 2005, Price voted against the East Asia Security Act, which would have allowed for sanctions to be placed on any country violating the [[Arms embargo#People's Republic of China|arms embargo on China]]. In 2007, Price co-sponsored the Syria Accountability and Liberation Act, which if passed, would have strengthened the sanctions imposed on Syria under the [[Syria Accountability Act]], and maintained those sanctions until [[Syria and weapons of mass destruction|weapons of mass destruction]] were seized in the country and dismantled. In 2008, Price voted in favor of the [[United States-India Nuclear Cooperation Approval and Non-proliferation Enhancement Act]].<ref name=\"Issues FoPo\">{{cite web|url=http://www.ontheissues.org/GA/Tom_Price_Foreign_Policy.htm|title=Tom Price on Foreign Policy|work=On the Issues|accessdate=October 28, 2017}}</ref>\n\n====Gun policy====\nPrice opposes [[gun control]]. Over the course of his congressional career, he consistently received high ratings from the [[National Rifle Association]] and its [[National Rifle Association#NRA Political Victory Fund|Political Victory Fund]], as well as from the [[Gun Owners of America]], while consistently receiving scores of 0 from the [[Brady Campaign to Prevent Gun Violence]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://votesmart.org/candidate/evaluations/11853/tom-price/37 |title=Tom Price's Ratings and Endorsements on Issue: Guns|work=Vote Smart|accessdate=November 19, 2016}}</ref>\n\nIn 2005, Price voted for the [[Protection of Lawful Commerce in Arms Act]], which protects [[firearms]] manufacturers and dealers from facing legal consequences, when crimes are committed with the use of their products.<ref name=\"Issues Guns\">{{cite web|url=http://www.ontheissues.org/GA/Tom_Price_Gun_Control.htm|title=Tom Price on Gun Control|work=[[On the Issues]]|accessdate=October 17, 2017}}</ref>\n\nIn 2007, Price co-sponsored the D.C. Personal Protection Act,<ref name=\"Issues Guns\"/> which would have repealed many of [[Washington D.C.]]'s local gun control regulations, over the protests of D.C.'s elected officials.<ref name=\"Issues Guns\"/><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.highbeam.com/doc/1P2-34963.html|author=Spencer S. Hsu|title=Gun Ban Opposition Called 'Slap in the Face'; Williams, Ramsey Assail Lawmakers|work=The Washington Post|date=June 29, 2005|accessdate=October 17, 2017}}</ref> Although the bill failed to become law, the 2008 [[Supreme Court of the United States|Supreme Court]] decision ''[[District of Columbia v. Heller]]'' found that the absolute prohibition of [[handgun]]s in D.C. was unconstitutional. Price praised this decision,<ref>{{cite web|url=https://votesmart.org/public-statement/353283/price-lauds-landmark-second-amendment-decision#.WeY8kmhSxPY|title=Price Lauds Landmark Second Amendment Decision|work=Vote Smart|date=June 26, 2008|accessdate=October 17, 2017}}</ref> as well as the Supreme Court decision reached two years later in ''[[McDonald v. City of Chicago]]'', which stated that the [[Second Amendment to the United States Constitution|Second Amendment]] applies to the states.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://votesmart.org/public-statement/529093/supreme-court-reaffirms-second-amendment-rights/?search=second%20amendment|title=Supreme Court Reaffirms Second Amendment Rights |work=Vote Smart |date=June 28, 2010 |accessdate=November 19, 2016}}</ref>\n\nIn 2009, Price supported the National Right-to-Carry Reciprocity Act, which if passed, would have made [[concealed carry]] permits issued by any state valid nationwide.<ref name=\"Issues Guns\"/>\n\n====Immigration====\nPrice believes that [[Illegal immigration to the United States|illegal immigrants in the United States]] should be [[Illegal immigration to the United States#Deportation|deported]], saying in 2005 of [[George W. Bush#Immigration|George W. Bush's plans for immigration reform]], \"Thinly veiled attempts to promote amnesty cannot be tolerated.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=http://go.galegroup.com/ps/retrieve.do?tabID=T004&resultListType=RESULT_LIST&searchResultsType=SingleTab&searchType=AdvancedSearchForm&currentPosition=14&docId=GALE%7CA145926107&docType=Article&sort=DA-ASC-SORT&contentSegment=&prodId=STND&contentSet=GALE%7CA145926107&searchId=R3&userGroupName=fairfax_main&inPS=true|author=Jay Bookman|title=Immigration: Bush's Border Border Strategy Misfires On All Fronts|work=The Atlanta Journal-Constitution|date=May 18, 2006|accessdate=November 1, 2017}} {{subscription required|via=Infotrac Newsstand}}</ref> In 2009, Price voted for the Birthright Citizenship Act, which if passed, would have revised the [[U.S. Constitution]]'s [[14th Amendment to the United States Constitution|14th Amendment]] to prevent children born to illegal immigrants in the country from attaining [[birthright citizenship]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ontheissues.org/GA/Tom_Price_Immigration.htm|title=Tom Price on Immigration|work=On the Issues|accessdate=November 1, 2017}}</ref>\n\n====LGBTQ rights====\nIn 2006, Price voted for the [[Marriage Protection Amendment]], which would have defined marriage as being between a man and a woman.<ref name=\"obamacarefoe\"/><ref name=\"Issues Civil Rights\">{{cite web|url=http://www.ontheissues.org/GA/Tom_Price_Civil_Rights.htm|title=Tom Price on Civil Rights|work=On the Issues|accessdate=October 18, 2017}}</ref> He was one of the proposed amendment's co-sponsors, when it was reintroduced in 2008.<ref name=\"Issues Civil Rights\"/> On multiple occasions, Price voted against the [[Employment Non-discrimination Act]], which if passed, would have expanded [[Employment discrimination law in the United States#Federal laws|federal anti-discrimination law]] to prohibit employers from discriminating on the basis of [[sexual orientation]] (several states already have such a protection and exceptions for religious organizations would have been allowed).<ref name=\"obamacarefoe\"/><ref name=\"Time LGBTQ\">{{cite web|url=http://time.com/4637046/donald-trump-hhs-lgbt/|author=Philip Elliot|title=LGBT Rights Group Opposes Donald Trump's Health Secretary Nominee Tom Price|work=Time|date=January 17, 2017|accessdate=October 18, 2017}}</ref><ref name=\"Issues Civil Rights\"/> In 2015, he co-sponsored the [[First Amendment Defense Act]], which if passed, would have prevented the federal government from penalizing businesses that deny services to [[same-sex couples]].<ref name=\"Huffington LGBTQ\">{{cite web|url=https://www.huffingtonpost.com/entry/nominee-for-hhs-secretary-comes-at-a-price-lgbtq-youth_us_588fb6e4e4b04c35d58350fa|author=Sheri Lunn|title=Nominee for HHS Secretary Comes at a Price LGBTQ Youth Cannot Afford|work=The Huffington Post|date=January 31, 2017|accessdate=October 18, 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://go.galegroup.com/ps/retrieve.do?tabID=T004&resultListType=RESULT_LIST&searchResultsType=SingleTab&searchType=AdvancedSearchForm&currentPosition=9&docId=GALE%7CA490808584&docType=Article&sort=Relevance&contentSegment=&prodId=STND&contentSet=GALE%7CA490808584&searchId=R1&userGroupName=fairfax_main&inPS=true|author=Emanuella Grinberg|title=The First 100 Days in LGBT Rights|work=CNN|date=April 29, 2017|accessdate=October 18, 2017}} {{subscription required|via=Infotrac Newsstand}}</ref>\n\nIn 2009, Price opposed the [[Matthew Shepard and James Byrd Jr. Hate Crimes Prevention Act]], which extended the scope of [[Hate crime laws in the United States#Federal prosecution of hate crimes|federal hate crime laws]] to include crimes in which individuals are targeted due to their sexual orientation, [[gender]], or [[gender identity]].<ref name=\"Huffington LGBTQ\"/><ref>{{cite press release|url=http://go.galegroup.com/ps/retrieve.do?tabID=T004&resultListType=RESULT_LIST&searchResultsType=SingleTab&searchType=AdvancedSearchForm&currentPosition=1&docId=GALE%7CA216099451&docType=Article&sort=DA-ASC-SORT&contentSegment=&prodId=STND&contentSet=GALE%7CA216099451&searchId=R3&userGroupName=fairfax_main&inPS=true|title=Congress Acts to Extend Hate Crimes to Cover Homosexuals|publisher=[[National Constitution Center]]|date=October 9, 2009|accessdate=October 18, 2017}} {{subscription required|via=Infotrac Newsstand}}</ref><ref name=\"Anti-LGBTQ\">{{cite press release|url=http://go.galegroup.com/ps/retrieve.do?tabID=T004&resultListType=RESULT_LIST&searchResultsType=SingleTab&searchType=AdvancedSearchForm&currentPosition=9&docId=GALE%7CA474184535&docType=Article&sort=Relevance&contentSegment=&prodId=STND&contentSet=GALE%7CA474184535&searchId=R2&userGroupName=fairfax_main&inPS=true|title=Five of Trump's Anti-LGBTQ Picks You Need to Know About|publisher=[[Human Rights Campaign]]|date=December 14, 2016|accessdate=October 18, 2017}} {{subscription required|via=Infotrac Newsstand}}</ref> Price also voted against the [[Don't Ask, Don't Tell Repeal Act of 2010]]<ref name=obamacarefoe/><ref name=\"Time LGBTQ\"/><ref>{{cite web|url=https://votesmart.org/public-statement/576891/price-statement-on-dont-ask-dont-tell-repeal#.WedyWmhSxPY|title=Price Statement on \"Don't Ask, Don't Tell\" Repeal|work=Vote Smart|date=December 15, 2010|accessdate=October 18, 2017}}</ref> and the [[Violence Against Women Reauthorization Act of 2013]], which extended the original bill's protections to cover same-sex couples.<ref name=\"Issues Civil Rights\"/><ref name=\"Huffington LGBTQ\"/>\n\nIn 2016, Price criticized the Obama administration's directive that allowed [[transgender]] students to use restrooms corresponding with their gender identity.<ref name=\"Time LGBTQ\"/><ref name=\"Huffington LGBTQ\"/><ref name=\"Anti-LGBTQ\"/> On Facebook, Price wrote, \"It is absurd that we need a 'federal restroom policy' for our nation's schools. This is yet another abuse and overreach of power by the #Obama Administration, and a clear invasion of privacy. Schools should not have to fear retaliation for failure to comply.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=http://politics.blog.ajc.com/2016/05/16/the-growing-bathroom-backlash-from-georgia-republicans/|author1=Greg Bluestein|author2=Tamar Hallerman|title=The Growing Bathroom Backlash from Georgia Republicans|work=The Atlanta Journal-Constitution|date=May 16, 2016|accessdate=October 18, 2017}}</ref>\n\nPrice consistently received scores of zero from the [[Human Rights Campaign]] (a gay rights organization) over the course of his congressional career, except for between 2007 and 2010, when he received 10% approval ratings.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://votesmart.org/candidate/evaluations/11853/tom-price/13#.WfOYiGhSxPY|title=Tom Price's Ratings and Endorsements on Issue: Civil Liberties and Civil Rights|work=Vote Smart|accessdate=October 27, 2017}}</ref>\n\n===Legislation sponsored by Price===\n[[File:Tom Price by Gage Skidmore 2.jpg|left|thumb|Price speaking on a panel about healthcare at the 2014 CPAC]]\nPrice is the sponsor of the [[Empowering Patients First Act]] (EPFA), which he first introduced in the 111th Congress and has reintroduced in each Congress since then. Originally intended to be a Republican alternative to Democratic efforts to reform the health care system, it has since been positioned by Price and other Republicans as a potential replacement to the ACA. The bill, among other things, creates and expands tax credits for purchasing health insurance, allows for some interstate health insurance markets, and reforms medical malpractice lawsuits.\n\nPrice introduced the [[Pro-Growth Budgeting Act of 2013]] on May 8, 2013.<ref name=1874sum>{{cite web|title=H.R. 1874 \u2013 Summary|url=http://beta.congress.gov/bill/113th-congress/house-bill/1874 | publisher=[[United States Congress]] | accessdate=March 28, 2014}}</ref> The bill would require the [[Congressional Budget Office]] to provide a macroeconomic impact analysis for bills that are estimated to have a large budgetary effect.<ref name=1874cbo>{{cite web|title=H.R. 1874 \u2013 CBO|url=http://cbo.gov/publication/45213|publisher=Congressional Budget Office | accessdate=March 28, 2014}}</ref> Price said it was necessary because of the Congressional Budget Office's current method of reviewing bills just to see what they would cost. Price said \"that is a model that has proven to be incapable of providing the type of macroeconomic diagnosis folks need to make sure we are pursuing policies that will help generate economic opportunity and bring down the nation's debt.\"<ref name=Housepushbudget>{{cite news | last=Kasperowicz | first=Pete | title=House to push budget reforms next week | url=http://thehill.com/blogs/floor-action/economics-trade/202010-house-to-push-budget-reforms-next-week| accessdate=April 1, 2014 | newspaper=The Hill|date=March 28, 2014}}</ref> H.R. 1874 has passed the House but has yet to become law.\n\n===Committee assignments===\n* '''[[United States House Committee on the Budget|Committee on the Budget]]'''\n* '''[[United States House Committee on Ways and Means|Committee on Ways and Means]]'''\n** [[United States House Ways and Means Subcommittee on Health|Subcommittee on Health]]\n** [[United States House Ways and Means Subcommittee on Human Resources|Subcommittee on Human Resources]]<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.gop.gov/member/tom-price/|title=Tom Price - gop.gov|work=gop.gov|access-date=2017-03-06|language=en-US}}</ref>\n\n===Caucus memberships===\n* [[Congressional Constitution Caucus]]<ref>{{cite web|title=Members|author=|url=https://congressionalconstitutioncaucus-garrett.house.gov/about-us/membership|format=|publisher=Congressional Constitution Caucus|date=|accessdate=8 May 2018}}</ref>\n\n==Involvement in U.S. Presidential elections==\nPrice endorsed [[Mitt Romney]] in the [[Republican Party presidential primaries, 2008|Republican Party's 2008 presidential primaries]]<ref>{{cite web|url=http://go.galegroup.com/ps/retrieve.do?tabID=T004&resultListType=RESULT_LIST&searchResultsType=SingleTab&searchType=AdvancedSearchForm&currentPosition=7&docId=GALE%7CA158805505&docType=Article&sort=Relevance&contentSegment=&prodId=STND&contentSet=GALE%7CA158805505&searchId=R1&userGroupName=fairfax_main&inPS=true|author=Tom Baxter|title=Presidential Candidates Line Up Georgia Support: Edwards, Romney Appear Strong, But Both Parties' Races 'Wide-Open'|work=The Atlanta Journal-Constitution|date=February 4, 2007|accessdate=October 30, 2017}} {{subscription required|via=Infotrac Newsstand}}</ref> and Newt Gingrich in the [[Republican Party presidential primaries, 2012|party's 2012 primaries]].<ref>{{cite press release|url=http://go.galegroup.com/ps/retrieve.do?tabID=T004&resultListType=RESULT_LIST&searchResultsType=SingleTab&searchType=AdvancedSearchForm&currentPosition=4&docId=GALE%7CA274817795&docType=Article&sort=Relevance&contentSegment=&prodId=STND&contentSet=GALE%7CA274817795&searchId=R7&userGroupName=fairfax_main&inPS=true|title=Slate of Georgia Officials Back Newt Gingrich for President|publisher=[[Newt Gingrich presidential campaign, 2012|Newt Gingrich for President, 2012]]|date=December 13, 2011|accessdate=October 29, 2017}} {{subscription required|via=Infotrac Newsstand}}</ref> In 2016, he supported [[Marco Rubio]] and initially opposed [[Donald Trump]], saying in March of that year that Trump would be \"dangerous for politics and the economy.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=http://go.galegroup.com/ps/retrieve.do?tabID=T004&resultListType=RESULT_LIST&searchResultsType=SingleTab&searchType=AdvancedSearchForm&currentPosition=2&docId=GALE%7CA447500200&docType=Article&sort=Relevance&contentSegment=&prodId=STND&contentSet=GALE%7CA447500200&searchId=R2&userGroupName=fairfax_main&inPS=true|author=Joseph Asaro|title=Rep. Congressman Talks Trump, Conservatism on Campus|work=[[UWIRE]]|date=March 26, 2016|accessdate=October 30, 2017}} {{subscription required|via=Infotrac Newsstand}}</ref> Despite this, once Trump became the Republican Party's presumptive nominee, Price switched his allegiance and corralled eight of his fellow House Republican [[United States Congressional committee#House committees|committee chairs]] into joining him.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.newyorker.com/magazine/2016/06/20/inside-the-gop-trump-dilemma|author=Ryan Lizza|title=Occupied Territory|work=[[The New Yorker]]|date=June 20, 2016|accessdate=October 30, 2017}}</ref> They released a group endorsement of [[Donald Trump]] for president on May 13, 2016, which stated, \"There is a path to winning in November, and it comes through unity. To solidify this partnership, we endorse Mr. Trump as the Republican nominee for President and call upon all Americans to support him.\"<ref>{{cite press release|url=https://www.donaldjtrump.com/press-releases/house-chairmen-endorse-donald-j.-trump-for-president1|title=House Chairmen Endorse Donald J. Trump for President|work=[[Donald Trump presidential campaign, 2016|Donald J. Trump for President]]|date=May 13, 2016|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160624003843/https://www.donaldjtrump.com/press-releases/house-chairmen-endorse-donald-j.-trump-for-president1|archivedate=June 24, 2016}}</ref> A month later, Price's efforts in getting those committee chairs to endorse Trump led the ''Washington Post'' to name Price as one of Trump's \"top six allies in Congress.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/news/the-fix/wp/2016/06/03/meet-donald-trumps-top-6-allies-in-congress/|author=Amber Phillips|title=The 6 People Donald Trump Trusts Most in Congress|work=The Washington Post|date=June 3, 2016|accessdate=October 30, 2017}}</ref>\n\n==Secretary of Health and Human Services==\n[[File:Tom Price official Transition portrait.jpg|thumb|150px|Price's official Trump Transition portrait]]\nOn November 29, 2016, Price was nominated for [[United States Secretary of Health and Human Services]] (HHS) by President-elect [[Donald Trump]].<ref name=\"washingtonpost.com\">{{Cite web |title=Trump picks Congressman Tom Price as health and human services secretary|website=Washington Post|access-date=2016-11-29| url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/news/post-politics/wp/2016/11/28/trump-picks-congressman-tom-price-as-health-and-human-services-secretary/}}</ref> On February 1, 2017, the [[United States Senate Committee on Health, Education, Labor and Pensions|Senate Health, Education, Labor, and Pensions Committee]] approved his nomination by a vote of 11\u20130 with all Democrats boycotting the vote, sending the nomination to the Senate floor.<ref name=\"cnn-committee-approves\">{{cite news|last1=Lee|first1=M. J.|title=Republicans suspend committee rules, advance Mnuchin, Price nominations |url=http://www.cnn.com/2017/02/01/politics/republicans-vote-to-suspend-committee-rules-advance-mnuchin-price-nominations/|accessdate=February 2, 2017|work=[[CNN]]|date=February 1, 2017}}</ref> On February 10, 2017, the Senate confirmed Price in a 52\u201347 vote.<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.congress.gov/nomination/115th-congress/33?r=21|title=PN33 - Nomination of Thomas Price for Department of Health and Human Services, 115th Congress (2017-2018)|date=2017-02-10|website=www.congress.gov|language=en|access-date=2017-03-06}}</ref>\n\nIn March 2017, Price endorsed the [[American Health Care Act of 2017]], a bill proposed by House Republicans that would repeal the [[individual shared responsibility provision|individual mandate]] and make several other major changes to the [[Patient Protection and Affordable Care Act]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.cnn.com/2017/03/06/politics/republicans-public-obamacare-plan/index.html|title=Republicans unveil bill to repeal Obamacare|last=CNN|first=Lauren Fox and Deirdre Walsh|website=CNN|access-date=2017-03-14}}</ref> When the [[Congressional Budget Office]] estimated that the American Health Care Act would insure 24 million fewer Americans than the Affordable Care Act by 2026 and reduce the federal deficit by $337 billion in the same span, Price said he disagreed \"strenuously\" with the report and found it \"not believable\".<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.politico.com/story/2017/03/trump-republicans-bad-position-obamacare-235994|title=White House calls CBO health care report bogus|work=POLITICO|access-date=2017-03-14}}</ref>\n\nIn April 2017, Public News Service reporter Dan Heyman was arrested by West Virginia police for \"aggressively breaching Secret Service agents\" and \"causing a disturbance by yelling questions\" related to proposed healthcare legislation at Price and [[Kellyanne Conway]].<ref name=arrest>{{Cite news|url=https://thinkprogress.org/reporter-arrested-for-asking-tom-price-if-domestic-violence-is-a-pre-existing-condition-under-59ec774321d2|title=Reporter arrested for asking Tom Price if domestic violence is a pre-existing condition under Trumpcare|work=Think Progress|access-date=2017-05-10}}</ref> Price said the arrest was \"not my decision to make\".<ref>{{cite news|last1=Schmidt|first1=Samantha|title=HHS secretary says police 'did what they felt was appropriate' in arresting a West Virginia journalist|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/news/morning-mix/wp/2017/05/10/west-virginia-journalist-arrested-after-asking-hhs-secretary-tom-price-a-question/|accessdate=June 12, 2017|publisher=Washington Post|date=May 11, 2017}}</ref>\n\nWhile he was HHS secretary he said that the [[individual mandate]] (a component of the Affordable Care Act which required all to purchase health insurance) increased the cost of health care.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.huffingtonpost.com/entry/tom-price-waiving-individual-mandate_us_597df94de4b02a4ebb760112|title=Tom Price Open To Waiving Obamacare's Individual Mandate|last=Marans|first=Daniel|date=2017-07-30|work=Huffington Post|access-date=2018-05-01|language=en-US}}</ref> However, in May 2018, while no longer HHS secretary, Price admitted that the repeal of the individual mandate would reduce participation of young and healthy individuals in the health insurance market and thus drive up the cost of health care for those remaining.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.usatoday.com/story/news/politics/onpolitics/2018/05/01/former-hhs-sec-price-repealing-individual-mandate-harm/568281002/|title=Former HHS Sec. Price: Repealing the individual mandate 'will harm' people insured through Obamacare|work=USA TODAY|access-date=2018-05-01|language=en}}</ref>\n\n===Private jet scandal===\n{{see also|Ben Carson office furnishing scandal}}\n\n[[File:C-37B (Gulf Stream 550).jpg|thumb|right|[[United States Air Force|USAF]] [[Gulfstream Aerospace|Gulfstream]] C-37B (military designation of the [[Gulfstream G550|G550]]). According to ''Politico'', Secretary Price and his wife flew on a C-37B to Africa and Europe in May&nbsp;2017 at an estimated cost of $311,418.25 for 30 hours of flight time.<ref name=\":7\"/>]]\nIn a series of reports in September 2017, ''[[Politico]]'' reported that since May 2017, Price had expended more than $1 million of department funds for his own travel on private charter jets and military aircraft.<ref name=\":7\">{{Cite news|url=http://www.politico.com/story/2017/09/28/tom-price-military-jets-europe-asia-hhs-243276 |author1=Pradhan, Rachana |author2=Diamond, Dan |title=Price took military jets to Europe, Asia for over $500K|publisher=Politico|access-date=2017-09-29}}</ref><ref name=review/> Many of the flights were between cities that are easily accessible by train or car and have frequent, low-cost commercial airline service.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Pradhan|first1=Rachana|last2=Diamond|first2=Dan|title=Price traveled by private plane at least 24 times|url=http://www.politico.com/story/2017/09/21/tom-price-private-charter-plane-flights-242989|accessdate=September 25, 2017|publisher=Politico|date=September 21, 2017}}</ref><ref name=precedent>{{cite news|last1=Diamond|first1=Dan|last2=Pradhan|first2=Rachana|title=Price's private-jet travel breaks precedent|url=http://www.politico.com/story/2017/09/19/tom-price-chartered-planes-flights-242908|accessdate=September 25, 2017|publisher=Politico|date=September 19, 2017}}</ref> Five Democratic members of Congress requested an inspector general's investigation into Price's use of private aircraft.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Pradhan|first1=Rachana|title=Democrats request inspector general investigate Price's use of charter planes|url=http://www.politico.com/story/2017/09/20/tom-price-charter-planes-democrats-response-242926|accessdate=September 25, 2017|publisher=Politico|date=September 20, 2017}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/national/how-tom-price-decided-chartered-private-jets-were-a-good-use-of-taxpayer-money/2017/09/22/7ca65e7c-9f42-11e7-8ea1-ed975285475e_story.html|title=How Tom Price decided chartered, private jets were a good use of taxpayer money|last=Davis|first=Aaron C.|date=2017-09-22|work=Washington Post|access-date=2017-09-22|language=en-US|issn=0190-8286}}</ref> Price's use of private planes was legal but was criticized by ethics experts as a misuse of taxpayer funding.<ref name=\"precedent\"/><ref name=\":6\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.npr.org/2017/09/28/554328239/price-says-he-will-pay-for-travel-on-private-planes |title=Price To Pay Portion Of Charter Flight Costs|work= [[NPR]].org |access-date=2017-09-29|language=en}}</ref> Price's spokesperson justified Price's use of private jets as a reasonable precaution, given that Price was once unable to attend an important meeting because a commercial flight was cancelled; ''Politico'' noted that the flight in question was cancelled because air travel had been virtually shut down in the region in question at the time, preventing even private jets from taking off.<ref name=\":5\" /> As a congressman in 2009, Price had criticized the use of private jets by government officials as \"fiscal irresponsibility run amok\".<ref name=\":5\">{{Cite news|url=http://www.politico.com/story/2017/09/22/tom-price-charter-jet-flights-243040|title=New details cast doubt on why Tom Price needed a private jet|work=POLITICO|access-date=2017-09-23}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.cnbc.com/2017/09/20/hhs-sec-tom-price-once-slammed-congress-private-jets.html|title=Tom Price, who reportedly used costly private jets, once slammed government planes as 'fiscal irresponsibility run amok'|last=Pramuk|first=Jacob|work=CNBC|date=2017-09-20|access-date=2017-09-22}}</ref>\n\nFollowing ''Politico's'' reporting on the matter, Price said that he would stop taking taxpayer-funded private jet flights pending a formal review by his department's inspector general.<ref name=\"review\">{{cite news|last1=Diamond|first1=Dan|title=Tom Price to halt taxpayer-funded travel on private jets|url=http://www.politico.com/story/2017/09/23/tom-price-private-jet-travel-review-hhs-243057|accessdate=September 25, 2017|publisher=Politico|date=September 23, 2017}}</ref> President Trump said that he was unhappy about Price's expenditures, but declined to state whether he would fire him.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.npr.org/2017/09/27/554041212/trump-not-happy-joins-critics-of-his-own-high-flying-cabinet-officials |title=Trump, 'Not Happy,' Joins Critics Of His Own Highflying Cabinet Officials|work=NPR.org|access-date=2017-09-28|language=en}}</ref> Price said later that September that he would reimburse taxpayers for $51,887, which he calculated as the cost of his seat on the more than $400,000 worth of charter flights.<ref name=\":6\" /><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/us-news/2017/sep/28/tom-price-health-secretary-private-flights-apology|title=Health secretary Tom Price apologizes for taking private flights for work|last=Jacobs|first=Ben|date=2017-09-28|work=The Guardian|access-date=2017-09-29|language=en-GB|issn=0261-3077}}</ref> He also vowed to discontinue the use of private charter flights for his travel.<ref name=Politico-170928>{{cite news |url=http://www.politico.com/story/2017/09/28/tom-price-private-charter-flights-reimburse-243267 |title=Price says he'll repay taxpayers for his private jet travel |author=Pradhan, Rachana |date=September 28, 2017 |newspaper=Politico |accessdate=September 29, 2017}}</ref> Later that day, it was revealed that the expenditures for Price's charter and military flights were higher than $1 million, including flights taken by Secretary Price and his wife to Europe and Africa. ''Politico'' also noted that Price had, in June 2017, defended a proposal to cut $663,000 from HHS's $4.9 million annual travel budget.<ref name=\":7\" />\n\nThe reports from ''Politico'' sparked a larger inquiry into the use of private planes by Trump administration officials. The [[United States House Committee on Oversight and Government Reform|House Oversight Committee]] started a bipartisan investigation led by Representatives [[Trey Gowdy]] (R-SC) and [[Elijah Cummings]] (D-MD) of all use of private and government-owned planes by non-elected government officials of the Executive Branch on September 26, citing {{UnitedStatesCode|5|5733}}, which states \"The travel of an employee shall be by the most expeditious means of transportation practicable and shall be commensurate with the nature and purpose of the duties of the employee requiring such travel.\"<ref>{{cite press release |url=https://oversight.house.gov/release/gowdy-cummings-investigate-federal-agency-travel/ |title=Gowdy, Cummings investigate federal agency travel |author= |date=September 27, 2017 |publisher=House Oversight Committee |accessdate=September 29, 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite letter |url=https://oversight.house.gov/wp-content/uploads/2017/09/2017-09-26-TG-EEC-to-Kelly-WH-Travel-due-10-10.pdf |recipient=General John F. Kelly |subject=Travel of non-elected officials in the Executive Office of the President |date=September 26, 2017 |publisher=House of Representatives, Committee on Oversight and Government Reform |accessdate=September 29, 2017}}</ref> Senator [[Chuck Grassley]] (R-IA) also sent a letter to the White House asking to \"detail what steps the administration has taken to ensure that cabinet secretaries use the most fiscally responsible travel in accordance with the public trust they hold and the spirit and letter of all laws, regulations, and policies that apply.\"<ref name=Politico-170928 /><ref name=Grassley-17>{{cite letter |url=https://www.grassley.senate.gov/sites/default/files/constituents/2017-09-28%20CEG%20to%20President%20Trump%20%28Price%20Cabinet%20Travel%29.pdf |author=Charles E. Grassley |recipient=President Donald J. Trump |subject=Price Cabinet Travel |date=September 28, 2017 |publisher=Office of Senator Charles E. Grassley |accessdate=September 29, 2017}}</ref>\n\nOn September 29, 2017, the White House announced that Price had resigned. Price, with a tenure of 231 days, became the shortest-serving Secretary of Health and Human Services in history.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.cnn.com/2017/09/29/politics/tom-price-resigns/index.html?adkey=bn|title=Price out as HHS secretary after private plane scandal|last=Producer|first=Kevin Liptak, CNN White House|work=CNN|access-date=2017-09-29}}</ref> On July 13, 2018, the [[inspector general]] of HHS issued a report finding that Price had repeatedly violated government travel rules, and had wasted at least $341,000 through his use of chartered jets and military aircraft.<ref name=\"nyt\">{{cite news |first=Robert |last=Pear |authorlink= |title=Health Secretary Tom Price Wasted $341,000 on Improper Travel, Inquiry Finds |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2018/07/13/us/politics/health-secretary-tom-price-wasted-money-improper-travel.html |work=[[New York Times]] |date=July 13, 2018 | page= |accessdate=2018-07-13}}</ref> The report recommended that the government attempt to recoup the money improperly spent on Price's travels.\n\n==Investment activity==\nIn 2015\u20132016, according to congressional financial disclosures, Price purchased shares totaling between $60,000 and $110,000 in value in [[Innate Immunotherapeutics]], an Australian [[biotech]] company. Innate has no approved drugs. The company has one [[multiple sclerosis]] drug in trial. Price participated in a private placement of more shares in August 2016, paying $.25 and $.34 per share. Price invested between $50,000 and $100,000. On January 13, 2017, the shares were valued at $1.31, giving Price an unrealized gain of 300%\u2013400% in a 6-month period. Price announced plans to sell several health care investments, including Innate, upon his confirmation as HHS Secretary.<ref>{{cite news |first=Thomas |last=Kate |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2017/01/13/health/innate-immunotherapeutics-tom-price.html |title=Australian Drug Maker Has Low Profile but Powerful Backers in Washington |publisher=New York Times |date=January 13, 2017 |accessdate=2017-01-15}}</ref>\n\nOn January 16, 2017, CNN reported that Price had purchased shares in [[Zimmer Biomet]], a medical devices company.<ref name=\":3\" /> Zimmer Biomet is an S&P 500 component, in that every S&P 500 ETF and numerous mutual funds often trade Zimmer Biomet.<ref name=\":4\" />  Price had a diversified, broker-directed portfolio of hundreds of stocks in which investment decisions were made by a Morgan Stanley financial advisor, and that advisor had purchased these shares, in addition to approximately 70 other stocks, as a part of a periodic portfolio re-balancing.<ref name=\":4\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.forbes.com/sites/jonhartley/2017/01/18/how-the-stock-trading-allegations-against-tom-price-are-completely-unfounded/#6217c6836781|title=How The Latest Stock Trading Allegations Against Tom Price Are Completely Unfounded|last=Hartley|first=Jon|work=Forbes|access-date=2017-03-07}}</ref> Less than a week after the stock purchase, Price introduced legislation, the HIP Act, that would delay a [[Centers for Medicare and Medicaid Services]] regulation until 2018. Industry analysts had warned that those regulations would significantly hurt the company's finances. Following the introduction of the HIP Act, Zimmer Biomet's [[political action committee]] made a donation to Price's reelection campaign.<ref name=\":3\">{{cite news |last1=Raju |first1=Manu |title=First on CNN: Trump's Cabinet pick invested in company, then introduced a bill to help it |url=http://www.cnn.com/2017/01/16/politics/tom-price-bill-aiding-company/ |publisher=[[CNN]] |date=January 17, 2017}}</ref>\n\nWhen questioned about his financial dealings during his confirmation hearing before the U.S. Senate on January 18, 2017, Price said, \"[e]verything that we have done has been above-board, transparent, ethical, and legal.\"<ref>{{cite news|last1=Lee|first1=MJ|last2=Luhby|first2=Tammy|title=HHS nominee Tom Price says financial dealings were legal |url=http://www.cnn.com/2017/01/18/politics/tom-price-hhs-hearing/ |accessdate=January 18, 2017 |publisher=[[CNN]] |date=January 18, 2017}}</ref>\n\nIn March 2017, [[ProPublica]] reported that U.S. Attorney [[Preet Bharara]] had been investigating Price's stock trades prior to Bharara's dismissal from his post by Donald Trump. Price said that he had not received any indication of a federal investigation into his stock trades.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Faturechi|first1=Robert|title=Fired U.S. Attorney Preet Bharara Said to Have Been Investigating HHS Secretary Tom Price|url=https://www.propublica.org/article/preet-bharara-fired-investigating-tom-price-hhs-stock-trading|accessdate=March 23, 2017|publisher=ProPublica|date=March 17, 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|last1=Faturechi |first1=Robert |title=Tom Price Intervened on Rule That Would Hurt Drug Profits, the Same Day He Acquired Drug Stock |url=https://www.propublica.org/article/tom-price-intervened-rule-hurt-drug-profits-same-day-acquired-drug-stock |accessdate=April 9, 2017|publisher=ProPublica|date=March 31, 2017}}</ref>\n\n==Personal life==\nPrice and his wife [[Betty Price (politician)|Betty]] reside in Roswell, and have one child, Robert Price.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://tomprice.house.gov/about/full-biography |title=Tom Price Bio |accessdate=September 30, 2013}}</ref> Betty served on the Roswell City Council and was elected to the [[Georgia House of Representatives]] in a 2015 special election to succeed the late [[Harry Geisinger]].<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.neighbornewspapers.com/view/full_story/26753475/article-Price-wins-District-48-election?instance=all |title=Price wins District 48 election |first=Katherine |last=Frye |publisher=Neighborhood Newspapers |date=July 14, 2015}}</ref> Price is a [[Presbyterian]].<ref name=\":2\">{{cite news | url=http://www.ncregister.com/daily-news/tom-price-trumps-pick-for-hhs-secretary-could-define-administrations-legacy | title=Tom Price, Trump's Pick for HHS Secretary, Could Define Administration's Legacy | publisher=[[National Catholic Register]] | author=Joan Frawley Desmondy | date=January 20, 2017}}</ref>\n\nHe is a past President of the Roswell [[Rotary Club]] and has served on the Board of the North Fulton [[Chamber of Commerce]].<ref>{{cite web | title=The Arena Rep. Tom Price | url=http://www.politico.com/arena/bio/rep_tom_price.html | publisher=[[Politico]] | accessdate=November 20, 2014}}</ref>\n\nAs of 2014, Price was estimated to have a net worth of $13.6 million.<ref>[https://www.opensecrets.org/pfds/summary.php?cid=N00026160&year=2014 OpenSecrets: Tom Price]</ref>\n\n==See also==\n{{Portal|Biography}}\n* [[Physicians' Council for Responsible Reform]]\n* [[Physicians in the United States Congress]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|30em}}\n\n==External links==\n{{commons category|Tom Price}}\n{{wikiquote}}\n* [https://www.hhs.gov/about/leadership/secretary/thomas-e-price-md/index.html Secretary of Health and Human Services Tom Price]\n* {{Dmoz|Regional/North_America/United_States/Georgia/Government/Federal/US_House_of_Representatives/Tom_Price_%5BR-6%5D|Tom Price}}\n* {{C-SPAN|Tom Price}}\n{{CongLinks|congbio=p000591|votesmart=11853|fec=H4GA06087|congress=tom-price/1778}}\n\n{{s-start}}\n{{s-par|us-ga-sen}}\n{{s-bef|before=Sallie Newbill}}\n{{s-ttl|title=Member of the [[Georgia State Senate|Georgia Senate]]<br>from the 56th district|years=1997\u20132005}}\n{{s-aft|after=[[Dan Moody (Georgia politician)|Dan Moody]]}}\n|-\n{{s-par|us-hs}}\n{{s-bef|before=[[Johnny Isakson]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title=Member of the [[List of United States Representatives from Georgia|U.S. House of Representatives]]<br>from [[Georgia's 6th congressional district]]|years=2005\u20132017}}\n{{s-aft|after=[[Karen Handel]]}}\n|-\n{{s-bef|before=[[Paul Ryan]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title=Chair of the [[United States House Committee on the Budget|House Budget Committee]]|years=2015\u20132017}}\n{{s-aft|after=[[Diane Black]]}}\n|-\n{{s-ppo}}\n{{s-bef|before=[[Jeb Hensarling]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title=Chair of the [[Republican Study Committee]]|years=2009\u20132011}}\n{{s-aft|after=[[Jim Jordan (Ohio politician)|Jim Jordan]]}}\n|-\n{{s-bef|before=[[Thaddeus McCotter|Thad McCotter]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title=Chair of the [[Steering and Policy Committee of the United States House of Representatives|House Republican Policy Committee]]|years=2011\u20132013}}\n{{s-aft|after=[[James Lankford]]}}\n|-\n{{s-off}}\n{{s-bef|before=[[Sylvia Mathews Burwell]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title=[[United States Secretar